{"title_page": "Andy Summers", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Andy Summers\n| image               = Andy_Summers_with_guitar_2015.jpg\n| caption             = Summers in 2015\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Andrew James Somers\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1942|12|31}}\n| birth_place         = [[Poulton-le-Fylde]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| origin              = [[Chipping Barnet]], [[London]], England\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[jazz]], [[jazz fusion]], [[New wave music|new wave]], [[new-age music|new-age]], [[avant-garde music|avant-garde]]\n| occupation          = Musician, composer, photographer\n| instrument          = Guitar, Vocals\n| years_active        = 1959\u2013present\n| label               = [[A&M Records|A&M]], [[Private Music]], [[RCA Victor]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Zoot Money's Big Roll Band]], [[Dantalian's Chariot]], [[Soft Machine]], [[the Police]], [[Robert Fripp]], [[Circa Zero]], [[Gustavo Cerati]], [[The Animals]]\n| website             = {{URL|www.andysummers.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew James Somers''' (born 31 December 1942), known professionally as '''Andy Summers''', is an English singer and guitarist who was a member of the rock band [[the Police]]. He was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] as a member of the band in 2003.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6314589.stm | title= The arresting case of The Police | website=[[BBC News]] | first=Mark | last=Savage | date=30 January 2007 | accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref> Summers has recorded solo albums, collaborated with other musicians, composed film scores, and exhibited his photography in galleries.\n\n==Early life==\nAndrew James Summers was born in [[Poulton-le-Fylde]], Lancashire.<ref name=\"shortbio\">{{cite book |last1=Welch |first1=Chris |title=The Complete Guide to the Music of The Police and Sting |publisher=Omnibus Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-7119-5302-4 |page=xii |quote=Andy Summers was born Andrew James Summers on December 31, 1942, in Poulton-le-Fylde, Lancashire}}</ref> During Summers' childhood, his family moved to [[Bournemouth]], then in Hampshire, England (it was reassigned to Dorset in 1974). After several years of piano lessons, he took up the guitar.<ref name=\"Huey\">{{cite web |last1=Huey |first1=Steve |title=Andy Summers |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/andy-summers-mn0000031173/biography |website=AllMusic |accessdate=17 February 2019 }}</ref> At an early age he played jazz guitar. In his teens he saw a concert by [[Thelonious Monk]] and [[Dizzy Gillespie]] in London that left a lasting impression.<ref name=\"Maxwell\">{{cite web |last1=Maxwell |first1=Jackson |title=Andy Summers Talks Echoplex Pedals, Recording with the Police and Jamming with Jimi Hendrix |url=https://www.guitarworld.com/artists/andy-summers-talks-echoplex-pedals-recording-with-the-police-and-jamming-with-jimi-hendrix |website=guitarworld |accessdate=17 February 2019 |date=26 October 2018}}</ref> By sixteen he was playing in local clubs and by nineteen he had moved to London with his friend [[Zoot Money]] to form [[Zoot Money's Big Roll Band]].<ref name=\"Huey\" />\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===Pre-Police career===\nSummers' professional career began in the mid-1960s in London as guitarist for the [[British rhythm and blues]] band Zoot Money's Big Roll Band, which eventually came under the influence of the [[Psychedelia|psychedelic scene]] and evolved into the [[acid rock]] group [[Dantalian's Chariot]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Soft machine|last=Bennett|first=Graham|page=141|isbn=978-0-946719-84-6|year=2005|publisher=SAF|location=London}}</ref> In September 1966, Summers was the first guitarist encountered by [[Jimi Hendrix]] after landing in the UK.<ref>{{cite book|title=Uncommon People: The Rise and Fall of the Rock Stars|last=Hepworth|first=David|page=101|isbn=978-0-593-07762-7|year=2017|publisher=Bantam Press/Transworld|location=London}}</ref> The young Summers is portrayed in fiction as one of the \"two main love interests\" in Jenny Fabian and [[Johnny Byrne (writer)|Johnny Byrne]]'s 1969 book ''Groupie'', in which he is given the pseudonym \"Davey\".<ref>{{cite journal|first= Roy |last= Wilkinson |title= \"All I ever got asked was, Which band is which, did you really do it, can I have a blow-job?\" |magazine= [[Select (magazine)|Select]] |date= July 1997 |page= 115}}</ref>\n\nAfter the demise of Dantalion's Chariot, Summers joined [[Soft Machine]] for three months and toured the United States. For a brief time in 1968, he was a member of [[the Animals]], then known as [[Eric Burdon]] and the Animals, with whom he recorded one album, ''[[Love Is (The Animals album)|Love Is]]''. The album features a recording of [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]]'s \"Coloured Rain\", which includes a 4{{nbsp}}minute and 15 second guitar solo by Summers. The LP also included a reworked version of Dantalion's Chariot's sole single \"Madman Running Through the Fields\".\n\nAfter five years in Los Angeles, mostly spent studying [[classical guitar]] and composition at [[California State University, Northridge]], he returned to London with his American girlfriend Kate Lunken.\n\nIn London, Summers recorded and toured with acts including [[Kevin Coyne]], [[Jon Lord]], [[Joan Armatrading]], [[David Essex]], [[Neil Sedaka]] and [[Kevin Ayers]]. In October 1975 he participated in an orchestral rendition of [[Mike Oldfield]]'s seminal \"[[Tubular Bells]]\".\n\nIn 1977, Summers was invited by ex-[[Gong (band)|Gong]] bassist [[Mike Howlett]] to join his band [[Strontium 90 (band)|Strontium 90]], but was soon coaxed away by future Police bandmates Sting and Stewart Copeland.\n\n===The Police===\n{{Main|The Police}}\nSummers achieved international fame as the guitarist for [[the Police]], which he joined in 1977, eventually replacing original guitarist [[Henry Padovani]]. Emerging from London's punk scene, the Police gained international renown with many hit songs, including \"[[Message in a Bottle (song)|Message in a Bottle]]\", \"[[Roxanne (The Police song)|Roxanne]]\", \"[[Don't Stand So Close to Me]]\", \"[[Every Breath You Take]]\", and \"[[Every Little Thing She Does is Magic]]\". During his time with the band, Summers twice won a [[Grammy Award]] for Best Rock Instrumental Performance, first in 1979 for \"[[Reggatta de Blanc]]\" (written with Copeland and Sting) and in 1980 for \"[[Behind My Camel]]\".\n\nAlthough Sting was the lead singer of the band, Summers occasionally contributed lead vocals, as in \"Be My Girl/Sally\" (1978), \"Friends\" (1980), \"Mother\" (1983), and \"Someone to Talk To\" (1983). Other notable Summers compositions from this period are \"Omegaman\" (which would have been released as the debut single from the 1981 ''[[Ghost in the Machine (The Police album)|Ghost in the Machine]]'' album had Sting not objected), \"Shambelle\" (1981), \"Once Upon a Daydream\", and \"Murder by Numbers\" both co-written with Sting (both 1983). In early 1984, after seven years together and record sales around eighty million, the Police disbanded.<ref>{{cite book|isbn=978-0-7119-5302-4|page=25|author=Welch, Chris |year=1996|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|title=The complete guide to the music of The Police and Sting}}</ref>\n\nThough not given songwriting credit, Summers wrote the guitar riff for \"Every Breath You Take\". It was recorded in one take with his 1961 [[Fender Stratocaster]] during the ''Synchronicity'' sessions. The song was number one for eight weeks. Sting won the 1983 Grammy Award for Song of the Year, and the Police won Best Pop Performance by a Duo Or Group With Vocal for this song. Summers provides an account of the session in his memoir, ''One Train Later''.<ref name=\"Memoir\">{{cite book |last=Summers |first1=Andy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xMDFPefQCHkC&dq |title=One Train Later: A Memoir |publisher=Macmillan |year=2007 |isbn=978-1429909297 |accessdate=29 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAs a member of the Police, Summers created a trademark guitar sound, which relied heavily on a chorus effect. He explained in 2017 how the sound came about:\n\n<blockquote>\"I created it sort of out of necessity; my mission was 'We\u2019re going to play for two hours each night as a trio,' so I wanted to have this fantastic, coloured guitar sound that was different for every song. So, I used the Echoplex, then a chorus, and a few other pedals\u2026envelope filters. As we went on, I acquired more stuff and got a [[Pete Cornish]] board. But what was driving it was to invade and push the edge of what the guitar was supposed to sound like, and make it really interesting over a show. So, it wasn\u2019t just one straight sound all the time. I could move it around. And it was appreciated by many millions of people (laughs). Of course, it\u2019s very tired and a bit 'retro' now; I\u2019m not very keen on it anymore. But in those days it was new, fresh, and exciting.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vintageguitar.com/32439/andy-summers/ |title=Andy Summers: Creating Light From Dark |author=Prato, Greg (2017) |work=[[Vintage Guitar (magazine)|Vintage Guitar]] |accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Post-Police===\n[[File:Andy Summers 1989.jpg|thumb|Summers in 1989]]\nSummers' solo career has included recording, touring, composing for films (including ''[[2010 (film)|2010]]'', ''[[Down and Out in Beverly Hills]]'', ''[[The Wild Life (1984 film)|The Wild Life]]'' and ''[[Weekend at Bernie's]]''), and exhibiting his photography in art galleries around the world.\n\nHe recorded the duet albums ''[[I Advance Masked]]'' (1982) and ''Bewitched'' (1984) with guitarist [[Robert Fripp]] of King Crimson, as well as duet albums with Victor Biglione, [[John Etheridge]], and Benjamin Verdery. His solo debut album, ''[[XYZ (Andy Summers album)|XYZ]]'', was released in 1987 and is the only non-instrumental album in his catalogue. Although it included pop material, such as the single \"Love is the Strangest Way\", it failed to dent the charts. In 1987 Sting invited Summers to perform on his second album ''[[...Nothing Like the Sun]]'', a favour the singer returned by playing bass on ''Charming Snakes'' (1990) and later contributing vocals to \"[['Round Midnight (song)|'Round Midnight]]\" on Summers' tribute album to [[Thelonious Monk]], ''Green Chimneys'', in 1999. In the mid-1990s Summers briefly returned to a more rock-oriented sound with ''Synesthesia'' (1995) and ''The Last Dance of Mr X'' (1997) before recording a string of jazz albums. \n\n[[File:AndySummers.jpg|thumb|Summers in 2006]]\n\n===The Police reunion===\n{{Main|The Police Reunion Tour}}\nDuring the 2007 Grammys Award show, the Police appeared, playing \"[[Roxanne (The Police song)|Roxanne]]\" and subsequently announcing that they would be going on tour. [[The Police Reunion Tour]] began in [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada on 28 May 2007, and continued until August 2008, becoming the third highest-grossing tour of all time.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/30/arts/music/30gram.html | work=The New York Times | first=Jeff | last=Leeds | title=The Police Will Kick Off the Grammys | date=30 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Circa Zero ===\nIn August 2013, Summers announced he had formed a new band, Circa Zero, with Rob Giles from [[the Rescues]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-polices-andy-summers-goes-back-to-basics-with-circa-zero-20130813 | title=The Police's Andy Summers Goes Back to Basics With Circa Zero | publisher = Rollingstone.com | author = Baltin, Steve | date = 13 August 2013 | accessdate=22 August 2013}}</ref> Originally, drummer Emmanuelle Caplette was also a member of the band.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mike-ragogna/silver-rails-and-circus-h_b_5035164.html | title= Silver Rails and Circus Hero: Conversations With Jack Bruce and Andy Summers | publisher = huffingtonpost.com | author = Ragogna, Mike | date = 26 March 2014 | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> Their debut show was 25 July 2013 at the [[El Rey Theatre]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://andysummers.com/2013/06/25/circa-zero-debut-show-el-rey-theatre-los-angeles/ | title=CIRCA ZERO DEBUT SHOW EL REY THEATRE LOS ANGELES | publisher = AndySummers.com | date = 25 June 2013 | accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> The band's debut album, ''[[Circus Hero]]'', was released 25 March 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://andysummers.com/2014/02/07/circa-zeros-circus-hero-march-25-2014-release-date/ | title=Circa Zero's Circus Hero March 25, 2014 Release Date | publisher = AndySummers.com | date = 7 February 2014 | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> It is titled after a [[malapropism]] of the band's name made by a radio disc jockey during an interview of Summers.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mike-ragogna/silver-rails-and-circus-h_b_5035164.html | title= Silver Rails and Circus Hero: Conversations With Jack Bruce and Andy Summers | publisher = huffingtonpost.com | author = Ragogna, Mike | date = 26 March 2014 | quote= I was on this early morning radio station and the guy said, \"Yeah, here he is with the new record from Circus Hero!\" and I went, \"Oh, god. It's Circa. Zero.\" But anyway I told Rob and he said, \"Yeah, we should call the album that.\" Just to be a little bit weird. I thought about the early Police albums where we had all these weird titles that kind of got people's attention. Might as well have fun with it. | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media | people = Summers, Andy and Kerr, Jim | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QYwMx54PndI | title = Andy Summers Interview Promo Movie & Circa Zero | publisher = youtube.com | date = 12 November 2012 | accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> The first single, \"Levitation,\" was released to US [[adult album alternative]] radio on 3{{nbsp}}March 2014;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allaccess.com/triple-a/future-releases |title=Future Releases on Triple A (AAA) Radio Stations |publisher=All Access Music Group |archiveurl=http://andysummers.com/2014/02/07/circa-zeros-circus-hero-march-25-2014-release-date/z |archivedate=27 February 2014}}</ref> and reached number 36 on the [[Japan Hot 100]] chart.<ref name=\"allmusic-billboard albums\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/circus-hero-mw0002616503/awards | title=allmusic ((( Circa Zero > Awards > Japan Hot 100 Singles )))| publisher=Billboard| accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Call the Police ===\n\nIn March 2017, Summers announced he had formed Call the Police, a Police tribute band, with two Brazilian musicians, Rodrigo Santos ([[Bar\u00e3o Vermelho]] aka Red Baron) on bass guitar and vocals and [[Joao Barone]] ([[Os Paralamas do Sucesso]]) on drums.\n\n===Material loss===\nOn 25 June 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Andy Summers among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=28 June 2019 |date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSummers was married to his first wife, the singer [[Robin Lane]], in 1968. They divorced two years later in 1970. He married his second wife, Kate Lunken, in 1973 and they had one daughter in 1978, Layla Zoe Summers. They divorced in 1981 although they would then remarry in 1985. In 1987, Kate and Andy's twin sons Maurice X and Anton Y were born.\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* Grammy Award, Best Rock Instrumental, \"Reggatta de Blanc\", 1979\n* Grammy Award, Best Rock Instrumental, \"Behind My Camel\", 1980\n* Rock and Roll Hall of Fame induction with the Police, 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rockhall.com/inductees/the-police/ |title=The Police: inducted in 2003 &#124; The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum |publisher=Rockhall.com |accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n* Chevalier of the [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]], with the Police, 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/culture/actualites/conferen/albanel/thepolice.html |title=C\u00e9r\u00e9monie de remise des insignes de Chevalier dans l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres \u00e0 Sting, Stewart Copeland, Andy Summers, du groupe The Police |date= 1 October 2007 |accessdate= 21 May 2013}}</ref>\n* Honorary doctorate, [[Bournemouth University]], 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bournemouth.ac.uk/graduationceremony/honorary_graduates/2008.html |title=2008 Graduates \u2013 Graduation Ceremony \u2013 Bournemouth University |publisher=Bournemouth.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n* Hall of Fame, ''Guitar Player'' magazine<ref name=\"Memoir\" />\n* Vote number one pop guitarist, five years, ''Guitar Player'' magazine<ref name=\"Memoir\" />\n* Guiding Light Award, Progressive Music Awards, 2016<ref name=\"Prog\">{{cite web|last1=Beaudin|first1=Jon|title=Jon Anderson & Andy Summers Big Winners at Prog Magazine's Progressive Music Awards - Smooth Jazz Now|url=http://smoothjazznow.com/music-news/jon-anderson-andy-summers-big-winners-at-prog-magazines-progressive-music-awards/|website=Smooth Jazz Now|accessdate=7 January 2017|date=2 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108190256/http://smoothjazznow.com/music-news/jon-anderson-andy-summers-big-winners-at-prog-magazines-progressive-music-awards/|archive-date=8 January 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 85th guitarist of all time, ''Rolling Stone'' magazine<ref>{{cite news |last=Browne |first=Davis |last2=Doyle |first2=Patrick |last3=Fricke |first3=Davis |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-guitarists-20111123 |title=100 Greatest Guitarists |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=23 November 2011 |accessdate=29 June 2015 }}</ref>\n* Lifetime Achievement Award, Gibson Guitar Awards, 2000<ref name=\"Gibson\">{{cite web|last1=Basham|first1=David|title=Andy Summers, Jeff Beck, Sheryl Crow Win Guitar Awards|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1425643/andy-summers-jeff-beck-sheryl-crow-win-guitar-awards/|website=MTV News|accessdate=7 January 2017|date=23 February 2000}}</ref>\n* Lifetime Achievement Award, Roland and [[Boss Corporation|BOSS, 2017]]<ref name=\"Roland\">{{cite web|title=Roland and BOSS Present Lifetime Achievement Awards to Andy Summers and Jean-Michel Jarre|url=https://www.rolandus.com/blog/2017/02/17/roland-and-boss-lifetime-achievement-awards-andy-summers-jean-michel-jarre/ |website=www.rolandus.com|accessdate=22 April 2018|date=17 February 2017}}</ref>\n* His autobiography ''One Train Later'' (2006) was voted music book of the year by ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' and was turned into the 2012 documentary ''Can't Stand Losing You: Surviving The Police''.<ref>{{cite book|isbn=978-0-415-93835-8|page=845|author=Frank W. Hoffmann, Howard Ferstle|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|location=New York, NY|title=Encyclopedia of recorded sound}}</ref> The documentary was released on DVD in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soundtrack.net/releasedates/2015/ |title=2015 Theatrical Movies |work=Soundtrack.net |accessdate=29 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Equipment==\n\n===The Police years===\n\n====Guitars====\n* [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]]\n** 1963 [[Fender Telecaster]] purchased from a student with most of the customization already done (as he told Fender when they wanted to make a tribute guitar)<ref>{{cite web|author=fendermusical |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2vzStQpEXHQ |title=Andy Summers Tribute Telecaster guitar demonstration video |publisher=Youtube.com |date=15 April 2008 |accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n** 1961 Dakota Red [[Fender Stratocaster]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.tiscali.it/andatta/ |title=The Unofficial Andy Summers Website |publisher=Web.tiscali.it |date= |accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n* Hamer\n** Standard, Sunbursts<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vintageguitar.com/1875/the-history-of-hamer-part-one/|title=The History of Hamer, Part One|last=Guitar|first=Vintage|date=2002-05-30|work=Vintage Guitar\u00ae magazine|access-date=2018-03-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* [[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]]\n** 1958 [[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]] [[ES-335]]\n** 1960 [[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]] [[Gibson Les Paul|Les Paul]]\n* [[Roland Corporation|Roland]]\n** [[Roland Corporation|Roland]] G-303 Guitar Synthesizer controller\n\n====Amps====\n* [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall]] Stack and [[Roland Jazz Chorus]] Combo\n\n====Effects====\n* [[Echoplex]] EP-2 [[Delay (audio effect)|Tape Delay]]\n* [[Electro Harmonix]] Electric Mistress [[Flanger]] and Deluxe Memory Man [[Delay (audio effect)|Delay]]\n* [[MXR Dyna Comp|MXR Dynacomp Compressor]]\n* custom [[Pete Cornish]] [[Guitar pedalboard]]\n* [[Roland Corporation|Roland]] GR-300 Guitar Synthesizer\n* [[Moog Taurus]] 205A Synthesizer Pedals\n\nThe above is a list of equipment used by Summers from the 1980s. Since that time he has built a collection of 200+ guitars and uses a wide variety of amplifiers and electronic equipment.\n\n==Photography==\nHis photography has been on display at art galleries around the world, such as\n* Leica Gallery, Los Angeles (2013)\n* Paris LA Independent Photo Show (2014)\n* [[photokina 2014|photokina]], Cologne (2014)\n* Shanghai Kunst-Licht Gallery2014 C-C-C Gallery, Beijing (2014)\n* Leica Gallery, Sao Paulo (2015)\n* Etherton Gallery, Tucson, Arizona (2015)\n\n==Discography==\n===Solo albums===\n* ''[[XYZ (Andy Summers album)|XYZ]]'' ([[MCA Records|MCA]], 1987)\n* ''Mysterious Barricades'' ([[Private Music]], 1988)\n* ''The Golden Wire'' (Private, 1989)\n* ''Charming Snakes'' (Private, 1990)\n* ''[[World Gone Strange]]'' (Private, 1991)\n* ''Synaesthesia'' (CMP, 1995)\n* ''The Last Dance of Mr. X'' (BMG/[[RCA Victor]], 1997)\n* ''Green Chimneys: The Music of Thelonious Monk'' (BMG Classics/RCA Victor, 1999)\n* ''Peggy's Blue Skylight'' (BMG Classics/RCA Victor, 2000)\n* ''Earth + Sky'' (Golden Wire, 2003)\n* ''Metal Dog'' (Flickering Shadow, 2015)\n* ''Triboluminescence'' (Flickering Shadow, 2017)\n\n===Collaborations===\n* ''[[I Advance Masked]]'' with [[Robert Fripp]] ([[A&M Records|A&M]], 1982)\n* ''Bewitched'' with Robert Fripp (A&M, 1984)\n* ''Invisible Threads'' with [[John Etheridge]] (Mesa, 1993)\n* ''Strings of Desire'' with Victor Biglione (R.A.R.E., 1998)\n* ''Splendid Brazil'' with Victor Biglione (R.A.R.E., 2005)\n* ''[[First You Build a Cloud]]'' with Ben Verdery (R.A.R.E., 2007)\n* ''Fundamental'' with [[Fernanda Takai]] (2012)\n* ''[[Circus Hero]]'' with Rob Giles as Circa Zero ([[429 Records]], 2014)\n\n===Film soundtracks===\n* ''The Wild Life'' (MCA, 1984)\n* ''[[2010 (film)#Music|2010]]'' (A&M, 1984)\n* ''Band of the Hand'' (1985)\n* ''[[Down and Out in Beverly Hills#Soundtrack|Down and Out in Beverly Hills]]'' (MCA, 1986)\n* ''The Craft'' (Columbia, 1996)\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Parade\"/\"Train\" with [[Robert Fripp]] (1984)\n* \"[[2010 (film)#Music|2010]]\"/\"To Hal and Back\" (1984)\n* \"Love is the Strangest Way\"/\"Nowhere\" (1987)\n\n===As band member===\n'''With [[The Police]]'''\n{{Main|The Police discography}}\n* ''[[Outlandos d'Amour]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Reggatta de Blanc]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Zenyatta Mondatta]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Ghost in the Machine (The Police album)|Ghost in the Machine]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Brimstone & Treacle (soundtrack)|Brimstone and Treacle]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Synchronicity (The Police album)|Synchronicity]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Every Breath You Take: The Singles]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Message in a Box: The Complete Recordings]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Live! (The Police album)|Live!]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[The Police (album)|The Police]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Certifiable: Live in Buenos Aires]]'' (2008)\n* ''Every Move You Make: The Studio Recordings'' (2019)\n\n'''With [[The Animals|Eric Burdon and the Animals]]'''\n* ''[[Love Is (The Animals album)|Love Is]]'' (1968)\n\n'''With [[Kevin Ayers]]'''\n* ''First Show in the Appearance Business'' (1996)\n* ''Too Old to Die Young'' (1998)\n* ''Yes We Have No Mananas, So Get Your Mananas Today'' (EMI/Harvest, 2009)\n\n'''With [[Kevin Coyne]]'''\n* ''[[Matching Head and Feet]]'' (Virgin, 1975)\n* ''Heartburn'' (Virgin, 1976)\n* ''In Living Black and White'' (Virgin, 1976)\n* ''Sign of the Times'' (Virgin, 1994)\n* ''On Air'' (Tradition & Moderne, 2008)\n\n'''With [[Dantalian's Chariot]]'''\n* ''Chariot Rising'' (Wooden Hill, 1996)\n\n'''With [[Eberhard Schoener]]'''\n* ''The Book'' (Ariola 1977)\n* ''Trance-Formation'' (Harvest/EMI Electrola 1977)\n* ''Video-Flashback'' (Harvest, 1979)\n* ''Video Magic'' (Harvest, 1978)\n\n'''With [[Strontium 90 (band)|Strontium 90]]'''\n* ''Police Academy'' (Pangaea, 1997)\n\n'''With [[Zoot Money's Big Roll Band]]'''\n* ''It Should Have Been Me'' (1965)\n* ''Zoot!'' (Columbia, 1966)\n* ''Transition'' (1968)\n* ''Were You There?'' (Indigo, 1999)\n* ''Fully Clothed & Naked'' (Indigo, 2000)\n\n===As guest===\n* [[Joan Armatrading]], ''[[Back to the Night]]'' (A&M, 1975)\n* [[Manuel Barrueco]], ''Nylon & Steel'' (Angel, 2001)\n* [[David Bedford]], ''The Odyssey'' (Virgin, 1976)\n* [[Gregg Bissonette]], ''Gregg Bissonette'' (Mascot, 1998)\n* [[Toni Childs]], ''[[House of Hope (album)|House of Hope]]'' (A&M, 1991)\n* [[Deeyah Khan]], ''Ataraxis'' (Heilo, 2007)\n* [[Jo Jo Laine]], ''Dancin' Man'' (Polydor, 1980)\n* [[Jon Lord]], ''[[Sarabande (album)|Sarabande]]'', (Purple, 1976)\n* [[Juicy Lucy (band)|Juicy Lucy]], ''Blue Thunder'' (Outer Music, 1996)\n* [[Roberto Menescal]], ''Bossa Nova Meets the Beatles'' (Deck/Jingle Bells 2017)\n* [[Anthony Moore]], ''Out'' (Virgin, 1976)\n* [[Paolo Rustichelli]], ''Capri/Mystic Jazz'' (Verve Forecast, 1991)\n* [[Neil Sedaka]], ''Live at the Royal Festival Hall'' (Polydor, 1974)\n* [[Michael Shrieve]], ''Stiletto'' (Novus/RCA/BMG, 1989)\n* [[Carly Simon]], ''[[Hello Big Man]]'' (Warner Bros., 1983)\n* [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], ''[[...Nothing Like the Sun]]'' (A&M, 1987)\n* [[Andrew York (guitarist)|Andrew York]], ''Centerpeace'' (2010)<ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web|title=Andy Summers Discography|url=http://andysummers.com/music/discography/|website=andysummers.com|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref>\n* Various, ''Twang!: A Tribute to Hank Marvin & the Shadows'' (Pangaea, 1996)\n* Various, ''Outlandos D'Americas: Tributo A Police (A Tribute to the Police)'' (1998)\n* Various, ''As Long As You're Living Yours: The Music of Keith Jarrett'' (BMG Funhouse/RCA 2000)\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Throb'' (William Morrow, 1983)<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Summers\n  | first = Andy\n  | title = Throb\n  | publisher = William Morrow\n  | year = 1983\n  | isbn = 0-688-02339-8\n}}</ref>\n* ''Light Strings'' (Chronicle, 2005)<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Summers\n  | first = Andy\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Light Strings\n  | publisher = [[Chronicle Books]]\n  | year = 2004\n  | isbn = 978-0-8118-4324-9\n}}</ref>\n* ''One Train Later'' (St Martins, 2006)<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Summers\n  | first = Andy\n  | title = One Train Later: A Memoir\n  | publisher = [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]\n  | year = 2007\n  | isbn = 978-0-312-37481-5\n}}</ref>\n* ''I'll Be Watching You'' ([[Taschen]], 2007)<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Summers\n  | first = Andy\n  | title = I'll Be Watching You: Inside the Police 1980\u201383\n  | publisher = Taschen America LLC\n  | year = 2007\n  | isbn = 978-3-8228-2764-2\n}}</ref>\n* ''Desirer Walks the Streets'' ([[Nazraeli Press]], 2008)<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Summers\n  | first = Andy\n  | title = Throb\n  | publisher = Nazraeli\n  | year = 2009\n  | isbn = 978-1-59005-256-3\n}}</ref>\n* ''The Bones of Chuang Tzu'' ([[Steidl]], 2018)<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Summers\n  | first = Andy\n  | title = The Bones of Chuang Tzu\n  | publisher = Steidl\n  | year = 2018\n  | isbn = 978-3-95829-403-5\n}}</ref>\n* ''A Certain Strangeness'' ([[University of Texas Press]], 2019)<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Summers\n  | first = Andy\n  | title = A Certain Strangeness\n  | publisher = University of Texas Press\n  | year = 2019\n  | isbn = 978-1-47731-890-4\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [https://andysummers.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.thepolice.com/ The Police official site]\n* [https://www.circazero.com/ Circa Zero official website]\n* [http://www.rockerzine.com/2015/08/andysummers/ Interview: \"Andy Summers: The Blessing and The Curse\" - Rockerzine.com 2015]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/berkshire/content/articles/2007/04/04/andy_summers_interview_feature.shtml BBC interview with Andy Summers including audio]\n* [http://www.dailyvault.com/article.php5?id=71 Book Review of Andy Summers' One Train Later]\n* {{imdb name|0814047}}\n\n{{The Police}}\n{{The Animals}}\n{{Soft Machine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Summers, Andy}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Poulton-le-Fylde]]\n[[Category:People from Chipping Barnet]]\n[[Category:British rhythm and blues boom musicians]]\n[[Category:California State University, Northridge alumni]]\n[[Category:Canterbury scene]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n[[Category:English jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male guitarists]]\n[[Category:English new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:English rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Jazz fusion guitarists]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:A&M Records artists]]\n[[Category:Private Music artists]]\n[[Category:Progressive rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:The Animals members]]\n[[Category:The Police members]]\n[[Category:Soft Machine members]]\n[[Category:Strontium 90 (band) members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Andy Summers\n| image               = Andy_Summers_with_guitar_2015.jpg\n| caption             = Summers in 2015\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Andrew James Somers\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1942|12|31}}\n| birth_place         = [[Poulton-le-Fylde]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| origin              = [[Chipping Barnet]], [[London]], England\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[jazz]], [[jazz fusion]], [[New wave music|new wave]], [[new-age music|new-age]], [[avant-garde music|avant-garde]]\n| occupation          = Musician, composer, photographer\n| instrument          = Guitar, Vocals\n| years_active        = 1959\u2013present\n| label               = [[A&M Records|A&M]], [[Private Music]], [[RCA Victor]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Zoot Money's Big Roll Band]], [[Dantalian's Chariot]], [[Soft Machine]], [[the Police]], [[Robert Fripp]], [[Circa Zero]], [[Gustavo Cerati]], [[The Animals]]\n| website             = {{URL|www.andysummers.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew James Somers''' (born 31 December 1942), known professionally as '''Andy Summers''', is an English singer and guitarist who was a member of the rock band [[the Police]]. He was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] as a member of the band in 2003.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6314589.stm | title= The arresting case of The Police | website=[[BBC News]] | first=Mark | last=Savage | date=30 January 2007 | accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref> Summers has recorded solo albums, collaborated with other musicians, composed film scores, and exhibited his photography in galleries.\n\n==Early life==\nAndrew James Summers was born in [[Poulton-le-Fylde]], Lancashire.<ref name=\"shortbio\">{{cite book |last1=Welch |first1=Chris |title=The Complete Guide to the Music of The Police and Sting |publisher=Omnibus Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-7119-5302-4 |page=xii |quote=Andy Summers was born Andrew James Summers on December 31, 1942, in Poulton-le-Fylde, Lancashire}}</ref> During Summers' childhood, his family moved to [[Bournemouth]], then in Hampshire, England (it was reassigned to Dorset in 1974). After several years of piano lessons, he took up the guitar.<ref name=\"Huey\">{{cite web |last1=Huey |first1=Steve |title=Andy Summers |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/andy-summers-mn0000031173/biography |website=AllMusic |accessdate=17 February 2019 }}</ref> At an early age he played jazz guitar. In his teens he saw a concert by [[Thelonious Monk]] and [[Dizzy Gillespie]] in London that left a lasting impression.<ref name=\"Maxwell\">{{cite web |last1=Maxwell |first1=Jackson |title=Andy Summers Talks Echoplex Pedals, Recording with the Police and Jamming with Jimi Hendrix |url=https://www.guitarworld.com/artists/andy-summers-talks-echoplex-pedals-recording-with-the-police-and-jamming-with-jimi-hendrix |website=guitarworld |accessdate=17 February 2019 |date=26 October 2018}}</ref> By sixteen he was playing in local clubs and by nineteen he had moved to London with his friend [[Zoot Money]] to form [[Zoot Money's Big Roll Band]].<ref name=\"Huey\" />\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===Pre-Police career===\nSummers' professional career began in the mid-1960s in London as guitarist for the [[British rhythm and blues]] band Zoot Money's Big Roll Band, which eventually came under the influence of the [[Psychedelia|psychedelic scene]] and evolved into the [[acid rock]] group [[Dantalian's Chariot]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Soft machine|last=Bennett|first=Graham|page=141|isbn=978-0-946719-84-6|year=2005|publisher=SAF|location=London}}</ref> In September 1966, Summers was the first guitarist encountered by [[Jimi Hendrix]] after landing in the UK.<ref>{{cite book|title=Uncommon People: The Rise and Fall of the Rock Stars|last=Hepworth|first=David|page=101|isbn=978-0-593-07762-7|year=2017|publisher=Bantam Press/Transworld|location=London}}</ref> The young Summers is portrayed in fiction as one of the \"two main love interests\" in Jenny Fabian and [[Johnny Byrne (writer)|Johnny Byrne]]'s 1969 book ''Groupie'', in which he is given the pseudonym \"Davey\".<ref>{{cite journal|first= Roy |last= Wilkinson |title= \"All I ever got asked was, Which band is which, did you really do it, can I have a blow-job?\" |magazine= [[Select (magazine)|Select]] |date= July 1997 |page= 115}}</ref>\n\nAfter the demise of Dantalion's Chariot, Summers joined [[Soft Machine]] for three months and toured the United States. For a brief time in 1968, he was a member of [[the Animals]], then known as [[Eric Burdon]] and the Animals, with whom he recorded one album, ''[[Love Is (The Animals album)|Love Is]]''. The album features a recording of [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]]'s \"Coloured Rain\", which includes a 4{{nbsp}}minute and 15 second guitar solo by Summers. The LP also included a reworked version of Dantalion's Chariot's sole single \"Madman Running Through the Fields\".\n\nAfter five years in Los Angeles, mostly spent studying [[classical guitar]] and composition at [[California State University, Northridge]], he returned to London with his American girlfriend Kate Lunken.\n\nIn London, Summers recorded and toured with acts including [[Kevin Coyne]], [[Jon Lord]], [[Joan Armatrading]], [[David Essex]], [[Neil Sedaka]] and [[Kevin Ayers]]. In October 1975 he participated in an orchestral rendition of [[Mike Oldfield]]'s seminal \"[[Tubular Bells]]\".\n\nIn 1977, Summers was invited by ex-[[Gong (band)|Gong]] bassist [[Mike Howlett]] to join his band [[Strontium 90 (band)|Strontium 90]], but was soon coaxed away by future Police bandmates Sting and Stewart Copeland.\n\n===The Police===\n{{Main|The Police}}\nSummers achieved international fame as the guitarist for [[the Police]], which he joined in 1977, eventually replacing original guitarist [[Henry Padovani]]. Emerging from London's punk scene, the Police gained international renown with many hit songs, including \"[[Message in a Bottle (song)|Message in a Bottle]]\", \"[[Roxanne (The Police song)|Roxanne]]\", \"[[Don't Stand So Close to Me]]\", \"[[Every Breath You Take]]\", and \"[[Every Little Thing She Does is Magic]]\". During his time with the band, Summers twice won a [[Grammy Award]] for Best Rock Instrumental Performance, first in 1979 for \"[[Reggatta de Blanc]]\" (written with Copeland and Sting) and in 1980 for \"[[Behind My Camel]]\".\n\nAlthough Sting was the lead singer of the band, Summers occasionally contributed lead vocals, as in \"Be My Girl/Sally\" (1978), \"Friends\" (1980), \"Mother\" (1983), and \"Someone to Talk To\" (1983). Other notable Summers compositions from this period are \"Omegaman\" (which would have been released as the debut single from the 1981 ''[[Ghost in the Machine (The Police album)|Ghost in the Machine]]'' album had Sting not objected), \"Shambelle\" (1981), \"Once Upon a Daydream\", and \"Murder by Numbers\" both co-written with Sting (both 1983). In early 1984, after seven years together and record sales around eighty million, the Police disbanded.<ref>{{cite book|isbn=978-0-7119-5302-4|page=25|author=Welch, Chris |year=1996|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|title=The complete guide to the music of The Police and Sting}}</ref>\n\nThough not given songwriting credit, Summers wrote the guitar riff for \"Every Breath You Take\". It was recorded in one take with his 1961 [[Fender Stratocaster]] during the ''Synchronicity'' sessions. The song was number one for eight weeks. Sting won the 1983 Grammy Award for Song of the Year, and the Police won Best Pop Performance by a Duo Or Group With Vocal for this song. Summers provides an account of the session in his memoir, ''One Train Later''.<ref name=\"Memoir\">{{cite book |last=Summers |first1=Andy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xMDFPefQCHkC&dq |title=One Train Later: A Memoir |publisher=Macmillan |year=2007 |isbn=978-1429909297 |accessdate=29 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAs a member of the Police, Summers created a trademark guitar sound, which relied heavily on a chorus effect. He explained in 2017 how the sound came about:\n\n<blockquote>\"I created it sort of out of necessity; my mission was 'We\u2019re going to play for two hours each night as a trio,' so I wanted to have this fantastic, coloured guitar sound that was different for every song. So, I used the Echoplex, then a chorus, and a few other pedals\u2026envelope filters. As we went on, I acquired more stuff and got a [[Pete Cornish]] board. But what was driving it was to invade and push the edge of what the guitar was supposed to sound like, and make it really interesting over a show. So, it wasn\u2019t just one straight sound all the time. I could move it around. And it was appreciated by many millions of people (laughs). Of course, it\u2019s very tired and a bit 'retro' now; I\u2019m not very keen on it anymore. But in those days it was new, fresh, and exciting.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vintageguitar.com/32439/andy-summers/ |title=Andy Summers: Creating Light From Dark |author=Prato, Greg (2017) |work=[[Vintage Guitar (magazine)|Vintage Guitar]] |accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Post-Police===\n[[File:Andy Summers 1989.jpg|thumb|Summers in 1989]]\nSummers' solo career has included recording, touring, composing for films (including ''[[2010 (film)|2010]]'', ''[[Down and Out in Beverly Hills]]'', ''[[The Wild Life (1984 film)|The Wild Life]]'' and ''[[Weekend at Bernie's]]''), and exhibiting his photography in art galleries around the world.\n\nHe recorded the duet albums ''[[I Advance Masked]]'' (1982) and ''Bewitched'' (1984) with guitarist [[Robert Fripp]] of King Crimson, as well as duet albums with Victor Biglione, [[John Etheridge]], and Benjamin Verdery. His solo debut album, ''[[XYZ (Andy Summers album)|XYZ]]'', was released in 1987 and is the only non-instrumental album in his catalogue. Although it included pop material, such as the single \"Love is the Strangest Way\", it failed to dent the charts. In 1987 Sting invited Summers to perform on his second album ''[[...Nothing Like the Sun]]'', a favour the singer returned by playing bass on ''Charming Snakes'' (1990) and later contributing vocals to \"[['Round Midnight (song)|'Round Midnight]]\" on Summers' tribute album to [[Thelonious Monk]], ''Green Chimneys'', in 1999. In the mid-1990s Summers briefly returned to a more rock-oriented sound with ''Synesthesia'' (1995) and ''The Last Dance of Mr X'' (1997) before recording a string of jazz albums. \n\n[[File:AndySummers.jpg|thumb|Summers in 2006]]\n\n===The Police reunion===\n{{Main|The Police Reunion Tour}}\nDuring the 2007 Grammys Award show, the Police appeared, playing \"[[Roxanne (The Police song)|Roxanne]]\" and subsequently announcing that they would be going on tour. [[The Police Reunion Tour]] began in [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada on 28 May 2007, and continued until August 2008, becoming the third highest-grossing tour of all time.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/30/arts/music/30gram.html | work=The New York Times | first=Jeff | last=Leeds | title=The Police Will Kick Off the Grammys | date=30 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Circa Zero ===\nIn August 2013, Summers announced he had formed a new band, Circa Zero, with Rob Giles from [[the Rescues]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-polices-andy-summers-goes-back-to-basics-with-circa-zero-20130813 | title=The Police's Andy Summers Goes Back to Basics With Circa Zero | publisher = Rollingstone.com | author = Baltin, Steve | date = 13 August 2013 | accessdate=22 August 2013}}</ref> Originally, drummer Emmanuelle Caplette was also a member of the band.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mike-ragogna/silver-rails-and-circus-h_b_5035164.html | title= Silver Rails and Circus Hero: Conversations With Jack Bruce and Andy Summers | publisher = huffingtonpost.com | author = Ragogna, Mike | date = 26 March 2014 | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> Their debut show was 25 July 2013 at the [[El Rey Theatre]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://andysummers.com/2013/06/25/circa-zero-debut-show-el-rey-theatre-los-angeles/ | title=CIRCA ZERO DEBUT SHOW EL REY THEATRE LOS ANGELES | publisher = AndySummers.com | date = 25 June 2013 | accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> The band's debut album, ''[[Circus Hero]]'', was released 25 March 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://andysummers.com/2014/02/07/circa-zeros-circus-hero-march-25-2014-release-date/ | title=Circa Zero's Circus Hero March 25, 2014 Release Date | publisher = AndySummers.com | date = 7 February 2014 | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> It is titled after a [[malapropism]] of the band's name made by a radio disc jockey during an interview of Summers.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mike-ragogna/silver-rails-and-circus-h_b_5035164.html | title= Silver Rails and Circus Hero: Conversations With Jack Bruce and Andy Summers | publisher = huffingtonpost.com | author = Ragogna, Mike | date = 26 March 2014 | quote= I was on this early morning radio station and the guy said, \"Yeah, here he is with the new record from Circus Hero!\" and I went, \"Oh, god. It's Circa. Zero.\" But anyway I told Rob and he said, \"Yeah, we should call the album that.\" Just to be a little bit weird. I thought about the early Police albums where we had all these weird titles that kind of got people's attention. Might as well have fun with it. | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media | people = Summers, Andy and Kerr, Jim | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QYwMx54PndI | title = Andy Summers Interview Promo Movie & Circa Zero | publisher = youtube.com | date = 12 November 2012 | accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> The first single, \"Levitation,\" was released to US [[adult album alternative]] radio on 3{{nbsp}}March 2014;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allaccess.com/triple-a/future-releases |title=Future Releases on Triple A (AAA) Radio Stations |publisher=All Access Music Group |archiveurl=http://andysummers.com/2014/02/07/circa-zeros-circus-hero-march-25-2014-release-date/z |archivedate=27 February 2014}}</ref> and reached number 36 on the [[Japan Hot 100]] chart.<ref name=\"allmusic-billboard albums\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/circus-hero-mw0002616503/awards | title=allmusic ((( Circa Zero > Awards > Japan Hot 100 Singles )))| publisher=Billboard| accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Call the Police ===\n\nIn March 2017, Summers announced he had formed Call the Police, a Police tribute band, with two Brazilian musicians, Rodrigo Santos ([[Bar\u00e3o Vermelho]] aka Red Baron) on bass guitar and vocals and [[Joao Barone]] ([[Os Paralamas do Sucesso]]) on drums.\n\n===Material loss===\nOn 25 June 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Andy Summers among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=28 June 2019 |date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSummers was married to his first wife, the singer [[Robin Lane]], in 1968. They divorced two years later in 1970. He married his second wife, Kate Lunken, in 1973 and they had one daughter in 1978, Layla Zoe Summers. They divorced in 1981 although they would then remarry in 1985. In 1987, Kate and Andy's twin sons Maurice X and Anton Y were born.\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* Grammy Award, Best Rock Instrumental, \"Reggatta de Blanc\", 1979\n* Grammy Award, Best Rock Instrumental, \"Behind My Camel\", 1980\n* Rock and Roll Hall of Fame induction with the Police, 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rockhall.com/inductees/the-police/ |title=The Police: inducted in 2003 &#124; The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum |publisher=Rockhall.com |accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n* Chevalier of the [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]], with the Police, 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/culture/actualites/conferen/albanel/thepolice.html |title=C\u00e9r\u00e9monie de remise des insignes de Chevalier dans l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres \u00e0 Sting, Stewart Copeland, Andy Summers, du groupe The Police |date= 1 October 2007 |accessdate= 21 May 2013}}</ref>\n* Honorary doctorate, [[Bournemouth University]], 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bournemouth.ac.uk/graduationceremony/honorary_graduates/2008.html |title=2008 Graduates \u2013 Graduation Ceremony \u2013 Bournemouth University |publisher=Bournemouth.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n* Hall of Fame, ''Guitar Player'' magazine<ref name=\"Memoir\" />\n* Vote number one pop guitarist, five years, ''Guitar Player'' magazine<ref name=\"Memoir\" />\n* Guiding Light Award, Progressive Music Awards, 2016<ref name=\"Prog\">{{cite web|last1=Beaudin|first1=Jon|title=Jon Anderson & Andy Summers Big Winners at Prog Magazine's Progressive Music Awards - Smooth Jazz Now|url=http://smoothjazznow.com/music-news/jon-anderson-andy-summers-big-winners-at-prog-magazines-progressive-music-awards/|website=Smooth Jazz Now|accessdate=7 January 2017|date=2 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108190256/http://smoothjazznow.com/music-news/jon-anderson-andy-summers-big-winners-at-prog-magazines-progressive-music-awards/|archive-date=8 January 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 85th guitarist of all time, ''Rolling Stone'' magazine<ref>{{cite news |last=Browne |first=Davis |last2=Doyle |first2=Patrick |last3=Fricke |first3=Davis |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-guitarists-20111123 |title=100 Greatest Guitarists |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=23 November 2011 |accessdate=29 June 2015 }}</ref>\n* Lifetime Achievement Award, Gibson Guitar Awards, 2000<ref name=\"Gibson\">{{cite web|last1=Basham|first1=David|title=Andy Summers, Jeff Beck, Sheryl Crow Win Guitar Awards|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1425643/andy-summers-jeff-beck-sheryl-crow-win-guitar-awards/|website=MTV News|accessdate=7 January 2017|date=23 February 2000}}</ref>\n* Lifetime Achievement Award, Roland and [[Boss Corporation|BOSS, 2017]]<ref name=\"Roland\">{{cite web|title=Roland and BOSS Present Lifetime Achievement Awards to Andy Summers and Jean-Michel Jarre|url=https://www.rolandus.com/blog/2017/02/17/roland-and-boss-lifetime-achievement-awards-andy-summers-jean-michel-jarre/ |website=www.rolandus.com|accessdate=22 April 2018|date=17 February 2017}}</ref>\n* His autobiography ''One Train Later'' (2006) was voted music book of the year by ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' and was turned into the 2012 documentary ''Can't Stand Losing You: Surviving The Police''.<ref>{{cite book|isbn=978-0-415-93835-8|page=845|author=Frank W. Hoffmann, Howard Ferstle|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|location=New York, NY|title=Encyclopedia of recorded sound}}</ref> The documentary was released on DVD in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soundtrack.net/releasedates/2015/ |title=2015 Theatrical Movies |work=Soundtrack.net |accessdate=29 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Equipment==\n\n===The Police years===\n\n====Guitars====\n* [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]]\n** 1963 [[Fender Telecaster]] purchased from a student with most of the customization already done (as he told Fender when they wanted to make a tribute guitar)<ref>{{cite web|author=fendermusical |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2vzStQpEXHQ |title=Andy Summers Tribute Telecaster guitar demonstration video |publisher=Youtube.com |date=15 April 2008 |accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n** 1961 Dakota Red [[Fender Stratocaster]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.tiscali.it/andatta/ |title=The Unofficial Andy Summers Website |publisher=Web.tiscali.it |date= |accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n* Hamer\n** Standard, Sunbursts<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vintageguitar.com/1875/the-history-of-hamer-part-one/|title=The History of Hamer, Part One|last=Guitar|first=Vintage|date=2002-05-30|work=Vintage Guitar\u00ae magazine|access-date=2018-03-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* [[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]]\n** 1958 [[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]] [[ES-335]]\n** 1960 [[Gibson Guitar Corporation|Gibson]] [[Gibson Les Paul|Les Paul]]\n* [[Roland Corporation|Roland]]\n** [[Roland Corporation|Roland]] G-303 Guitar Synthesizer controller\n\n====Amps====\n* [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall]] Stack and [[Roland Jazz Chorus]] Combo\n\n====Effects====\n* [[Echoplex]] EP-2 [[Delay (audio effect)|Tape Delay]]\n* [[Electro Harmonix]] Electric Mistress [[Flanger]] and Deluxe Memory Man [[Delay (audio effect)|Delay]]\n* [[MXR Dyna Comp|MXR Dynacomp Compressor]]\n* custom [[Pete Cornish]] [[Guitar pedalboard]]\n* [[Roland Corporation|Roland]] GR-300 Guitar Synthesizer\n* [[Moog Taurus]] 205A Synthesizer Pedals\n\nThe above is a list of equipment used by Summers from the 1980s. Since that time he has built a collection of 200+ guitars and uses a wide variety of amplifiers and electronic equipment.\n\n==Photography==\nHis photography has been on display at art galleries around the world, such as\n* Leica Gallery, Los Angeles (2013)\n* Paris LA Independent Photo Show (2014)\n* [[photokina 2014|photokina]], Cologne (2014)\n* Shanghai Kunst-Licht Gallery2014 C-C-C Gallery, Beijing (2014)\n* Leica Gallery, Sao Paulo (2015)\n* Etherton Gallery, Tucson, Arizona (2015)\n\n==Discography==\n===Solo albums===\n* ''[[XYZ (Andy Summers album)|XYZ]]'' ([[