{"title_page": "Howard Leese", "text_new": "{{infobox musical artist\n|name         = Howard Leese\n|background   = solo_singer\n|image        = Howie2.jpg\n|caption      = Howard on stage with [[Paul Rodgers|The Paul Rodgers Band]] in 2009\n|image_size   = 250\n|landscape    = yes\n|birth_name   = Howard M. Leese\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1951|6|13}}\n|birth_place  = [[Hollywood]], [[California]], United States\n|origin       = [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n|instrument   = [[Guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]], [[Singing|backing vocals]]\n|genre        = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[hard rock]]\n|associated_acts =[[Heart (band)|Heart]]<br>[[The Zoo (Los Angeles band)|The Zoo]]<br>[[Dixon House Band]]<br>[[Paul Rodgers]]<br>[[Bad Company]]<br>[[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]\n|years_active = 1966\u2013present \n|occupation = [[Guitarist]], [[record producer|producer]], [[singer-songwriter]], [[performer]]\n|website    = \n}}\n'''Howard M. Leese''' (born June 13, 1951 in [[Hollywood]], [[California]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[guitarist]], record producer, and musical director who played with [[Heart (band)|Heart]] as guitarist and keyboardist for 23 years (1975 through 1998). He continues to record and tour as a solo artist, and as guitarist with [[Paul Rodgers|The Paul Rodgers Band]] and [[Bad Company]].  He is currently performing in the Las Vegas production of ''[[Raiding the Rock Vault]]''.\n\n==Career==\nHoward received his inspiration to pick up the guitar during the 1960s after seeing [[Dick Dale]], the guitarist in the surf band \"the Del-Tones\", and feeling the excitement from his playing. He studied violin and music theory at the [[Los Angeles City College|City College, Los Angeles]], and also played in a band called The Zoo.\n\nLeese had his first recording contract with [[Ed Cobb]]'s Sunburst label<ref>Not Sunburst Records of Huntsville, Alabama, but a Los Angeles based company.</ref> at the age of 15, as the band ''The Zoo'' with friend and drummer [[Mike Flicker]].  Later, when Flicker went to work for Jack Herschorn at [[Mushroom Studios]] in [[Vancouver]], Leese went with him as a production manager.  While there, he and Shelly Siegel started [[Mushroom Records (Canada)|Mushroom Records]].\n\nIt was at Mushroom Studios in 1974 that Leese helped produce a demo for [[Heart (band)|Heart]].  The next year, Mushroom Records signed Heart and released the group's first album ''[[Dreamboat Annie]]'' which Flicker produced.  Leese was assistant producer on the album, and was asked to join the band later that year. He played with the band until 1998, when the Wilson sisters put the band on hiatus for several years to pursue other projects and devote more time to their personal lives. Leese was Heart's guitarist, backing vocalist, keyboard player (best known for playing the Mini-Moog solo on the hit song \"Magic Man\") and song arranger. Aside from the Wilson sisters, Leese is the longest serving member of Heart.  Even though he left on good terms with the Wilsons, Leese has been vocal about his dislike of more recent versions of Heart indicating in a 2007 interview that the then-current lineup \"stinks\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Itter|first1=Scott|title=Secret Weapon: The Howard Leese Interview|url=http://www.drmusic.org/Howard_Leese__1.html|website=drmusic.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 he joined the [[Paul Rodgers|Paul Rodgers Band]].  He continues to tour with them as with [[Bad Company]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/guitarist-howard-leese-discusses-raiding-rock-vault-heart-and-bad-company|title=Guitarist Howard Leese Discusses 'Raiding the Rock Vault,' Heart and Bad Company|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAs of May, 2013, when not touring, Howard is performing in ''[[Raiding the Rock Vault]]'' which originated at the [[LVH Hotel]] but is now in residency at Vinyl at the [[Hard Rock Hotel and Casino (Las Vegas)|Hard Rock Hotel and Casino]] in Las Vegas.  As of Feb 2020, Raiding the Rock Vault is now playing at Rio Hotel in Las Vegas. \n\nHe splits his time between homes in [[Malibu, California]] and [[Kent, Washington]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roth|first1=Greg|title=The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame has Heart (Interviews)|url=http://seattlemusicinsider.com/2013/04/18/the-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-has-heart-video-and-audio-interviews/|website=seattlemusicinsider.com|publisher=SMI|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Solo career==\n2009 saw the release of Leese's first solo effort, ''Secret Weapon'', through [[Frontiers Records]]. The disc includes special guest appearances by [[Joe Lynn Turner]], Paul Rodgers, [[Jimi Jamison]] and [[Keith Emerson]].\n\n==Instruments==\nHoward is a longtime player and endorser of [[PRS Guitars|Paul Reed Smith Guitars]].{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} In 2009, Paul Reed Smith announced and launched the \"Howard Leese Limited Edition Golden Eagle\" in tribute to the #1 guitar that he played on stage for over 15 years.<ref>[http://www.prsguitars.com/artist/profiles/howardleese/ \"Howard Leese\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104081307/http://www.prsguitars.com/artist/profiles/howardleese/ |date=2013-11-04 }}.</ref> In the late 1970s, he performed live with the rare [[Sardonyx (guitar)|Sardonyx]] guitar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flight of the Sardonyx|last=Kehew|first=Brian|date=May 2012|work=[[Vintage Guitar (magazine)|Vintage Guitar]]|pages=46\u201347}}</ref>\n\nHoward has used and endorsed [[Toadworks]] guitar effects since 2004. In January 2009, ToadWorks USA released the Howard Leese Signature Model analog [[flanger]] named Barracuda, after the [[Barracuda (song)|Heart song]] of the same name).{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==HML Guitars==\nHML Guitars was founded in 1994 by Howard Leese.  As a woodworker and luthier, he participated in all aspects of construction as well as quality control.  HML guitars were totally hand-built in Seattle by luthier Jack Pimentel.  Pimentel has continued to build hand-crafted custom guitars under his own brand JP Guitars.<ref>[http://www.jpguitars.com/ JP Guitars], www.jpguitars.com</ref>\n\n==Albums==\n\n; The Zoo : \n*''The Zoo Presents Chocolate Moose'' (1968) -- by [[The Zoo (Los Angeles band)|The Zoo]]<ref>[http://lost-in-tyme.blogspot.com/2007/07/zoo-1968-presents-chocolate-mouse.html The Zoo Presents Chocolate Moose (1968)], Lost-In-Tyme, July 2007.</ref>\n\n; Mad Dog : \n*''Dawn of the Seventh Sun'' (1969) -- by Mad Dog<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/dawn-of-the-seventh-sun-mw0001005301|title=Dawn of the Seventh Sun - Mad Dog - Songs, Reviews, Credits - AllMusic|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\n; [[Heart (band)|Heart]] :\n*''[[Dreamboat Annie]]'' (1975) \n*''[[Little Queen]]'' (1977) \n*''[[Magazine (Heart album)|Magazine]]'' (1978) \n*''[[Dog & Butterfly (album)|Dog and Butterfly]]'' (1978) \n*''[[Bebe Le Strange]]'' (1980) \n*''[[Private Audition]]'' (1982) \n*''[[Passionworks]]'' (1983) \n*''[[Heart (Heart album)|Heart]]'' (1985) \n*''[[Bad Animals]]'' (1987) \n*''[[Brigade (album)|Brigade]]'' (1990) \n*''[[Desire Walks On]]'' (1993) \n*''[[The Road Home (Heart album)|The Road Home]]'' (1995)\n\n; [[Dixon House Band]] : \n*''[[Fighting Alone]]'' (1979) \n*''[[Masked Madness]]'' (1981)\n\n; [[Paul Rodgers]] :\n*''[[Live in Glasgow (Paul Rodgers album)|Paul Rodgers: Live in Glasgow]]'' (2007)\n\n; [[Bad Company]] : \n*''[[Hard Rock Live (album)|Hard Rock Live]]'' (2010) \n*''[[Live at Wembley (Bad Company album)|Live at Wembley]]'' (2011)\n\n; Solo :\n*''[[Secret Weapon (Howard Leese album)|Secret Weapon]]'' (2009) - With [[Keith Emerson]] and Paul Rodgers.\n\n; Others :\n*''[[Randy Meisner (1982 album)|Randy Meisner]]'' (1982) -- by [[Randy Meisner]]\n*''[[The Thirteenth Dream]] (aka Spirit of '84)'' (1984) -- by [[Spirit (band)|Spirit]]\n*''[[Dangerous Curves (album)|Dangerous Curves]]'' (1991) -- by [[Lita Ford]]\n*''There Must Be A Place'' (1993) -- by Bananafish<ref>[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950106&slug=2097990 Bananafish: Energetic Sound, Hopeful Music], 6 January 1995, The Seattle Times.</ref>\n* ''The Yellow Album'' by The Simpsons. Lead & rhythm guitar on ''Sisters Are Doin' It For Themselves'' : https://www.discogs.com/fr/The-Simpsons-The-Yellow-Album/release/1092354\n\n==Notes==\n<!-- [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] -->\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n*Fjestad S.P. (ed.) Zachary R. (2008) ''Blue Book of Electric Guitars'' 11th Edition, Illustrated, Publisher: Alfred Publishing, {{ISBN|1-886768-73-0}}, {{ISBN|978-1-886768-73-4}} pp.&nbsp;599\n*York, William (ed.) (1982) \"Leese, Howard\" ''Who's Who in Rock Music'' Charles Scribner's Sons, New York, {{ISBN|0-684-17343-3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070807102424/http://www.howardleese.com/apps/content/biography.asp \"Howard Leese biography\"] Official Website of Howard Leese\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110717084604/http://brigade.monger.net/howie.html \"Howie's Page\"], ''BebeLeStrange's Ann and Nancy Wilson Site'' by Todd Kinzey\n*{{Cite web |url=http://207.168.168.83/interviews01/howard_leese_interview.htm |title=Interview with Howard Leese |access-date=July 30, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050406201546/http://207.168.168.83/interviews01/howard_leese_interview.htm |archive-date=April 6, 2005 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }} ''Classic Rock Revisited''\n\n{{Heart (band)}}\n{{Bad Company}}\n{{Foreigner}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leese, Howard}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Record producers from California]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Music directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Hollywood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Heart (band) members]]\n[[Category:Foreigner (band) members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American keyboardists]]\n[[Category:Frontiers Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox musical artist\n|name         = Howard Leese\n|background   = solo_singer\n|image        = Howie2.jpg\n|caption      = Howard on stage with [[Paul Rodgers|The Paul Rodgers Band]] in 2009\n|image_size   = 250\n|landscape    = yes\n|birth_name   = Howard M. Leese\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1951|6|13}}\n|birth_place  = [[Hollywood]], [[California]], United States\n|origin       = [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n|instrument   = [[Guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]], [[Singing|backing vocals]]\n|genre        = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[hard rock]]\n|associated_acts =[[Heart (band)|Heart]]<br>[[The Zoo (Los Angeles band)|The Zoo]]<br>[[Dixon House Band]]<br>[[Paul Rodgers]]<br>[[Bad Company]]\n|years_active = 1966\u2013present \n|occupation = [[Guitarist]], [[record producer|producer]], [[singer-songwriter]], [[performer]]\n|website    = \n}}\n'''Howard M. Leese''' (born June 13, 1951 in [[Hollywood]], [[California]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[guitarist]], record producer, and musical director who played with [[Heart (band)|Heart]] as guitarist and keyboardist for 23 years (1975 through 1998). He continues to record and tour as a solo artist, and as guitarist with [[Paul Rodgers|The Paul Rodgers Band]] and [[Bad Company]].  He is currently performing in the Las Vegas production of ''[[Raiding the Rock Vault]]''.\n\n==Career==\nHoward received his inspiration to pick up the guitar during the 1960s after seeing [[Dick Dale]], the guitarist in the surf band \"the Del-Tones\", and feeling the excitement from his playing. He studied violin and music theory at the [[Los Angeles City College|City College, Los Angeles]], and also played in a band called The Zoo.\n\nLeese had his first recording contract with [[Ed Cobb]]'s Sunburst label<ref>Not Sunburst Records of Huntsville, Alabama, but a Los Angeles based company.</ref> at the age of 15, as the band ''The Zoo'' with friend and drummer [[Mike Flicker]].  Later, when Flicker went to work for Jack Herschorn at [[Mushroom Studios]] in [[Vancouver]], Leese went with him as a production manager.  While there, he and Shelly Siegel started [[Mushroom Records (Canada)|Mushroom Records]].\n\nIt was at Mushroom Studios in 1974 that Leese helped produce a demo for [[Heart (band)|Heart]].  The next year, Mushroom Records signed Heart and released the group's first album ''[[Dreamboat Annie]]'' which Flicker produced.  Leese was assistant producer on the album, and was asked to join the band later that year. He played with the band until 1998, when the Wilson sisters put the band on hiatus for several years to pursue other projects and devote more time to their personal lives. Leese was Heart's guitarist, backing vocalist, keyboard player (best known for playing the Mini-Moog solo on the hit song \"Magic Man\") and song arranger. Aside from the Wilson sisters, Leese is the longest serving member of Heart.  Even though he left on good terms with the Wilsons, Leese has been vocal about his dislike of more recent versions of Heart indicating in a 2007 interview that the then-current lineup \"stinks\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Itter|first1=Scott|title=Secret Weapon: The Howard Leese Interview|url=http://www.drmusic.org/Howard_Leese__1.html|website=drmusic.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 he joined the [[Paul Rodgers|Paul Rodgers Band]].  He continues to tour with them as with [[Bad Company]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/guitarist-howard-leese-discusses-raiding-rock-vault-heart-and-bad-company|title=Guitarist Howard Leese Discusses 'Raiding the Rock Vault,' Heart and Bad Company|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAs of May, 2013, when not touring, Howard is performing in ''[[Raiding the Rock Vault]]'' which originated at the [[LVH Hotel]] but is now in residency at Vinyl at the [[Hard Rock Hotel and Casino (Las Vegas)|Hard Rock Hotel and Casino]] in Las Vegas.  As of Feb 2020, Raiding the Rock Vault is now playing at Rio Hotel in Las Vegas. \n\nHe splits his time between homes in [[Malibu, California]] and [[Kent, Washington]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roth|first1=Greg|title=The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame has Heart (Interviews)|url=http://seattlemusicinsider.com/2013/04/18/the-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-has-heart-video-and-audio-interviews/|website=seattlemusicinsider.com|publisher=SMI|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Solo career==\n2009 saw the release of Leese's first solo effort, ''Secret Weapon'', through [[Frontiers Records]]. The disc includes special guest appearances by [[Joe Lynn Turner]], Paul Rodgers, [[Jimi Jamison]] and [[Keith Emerson]].\n\n==Instruments==\nHoward is a longtime player and endorser of [[PRS Guitars|Paul Reed Smith Guitars]].{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} In 2009, Paul Reed Smith announced and launched the \"Howard Leese Limited Edition Golden Eagle\" in tribute to the #1 guitar that he played on stage for over 15 years.<ref>[http://www.prsguitars.com/artist/profiles/howardleese/ \"Howard Leese\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104081307/http://www.prsguitars.com/artist/profiles/howardleese/ |date=2013-11-04 }}.</ref> In the late 1970s, he performed live with the rare [[Sardonyx (guitar)|Sardonyx]] guitar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flight of the Sardonyx|last=Kehew|first=Brian|date=May 2012|work=[[Vintage Guitar (magazine)|Vintage Guitar]]|pages=46\u201347}}</ref>\n\nHoward has used and endorsed [[Toadworks]] guitar effects since 2004. In January 2009, ToadWorks USA released the Howard Leese Signature Model analog [[flanger]] named Barracuda, after the [[Barracuda (song)|Heart song]] of the same name).{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==HML Guitars==\nHML Guitars was founded in 1994 by Howard Leese.  As a woodworker and luthier, he participated in all aspects of construction as well as quality control.  HML guitars were totally hand-built in Seattle by luthier Jack Pimentel.  Pimentel has continued to build hand-crafted custom guitars under his own brand JP Guitars.<ref>[http://www.jpguitars.com/ JP Guitars], www.jpguitars.com</ref>\n\n==Albums==\n\n; The Zoo : \n*''The Zoo Presents Chocolate Moose'' (1968) -- by [[The Zoo (Los Angeles band)|The Zoo]]<ref>[http://lost-in-tyme.blogspot.com/2007/07/zoo-1968-presents-chocolate-mouse.html The Zoo Presents Chocolate Moose (1968)], Lost-In-Tyme, July 2007.</ref>\n\n; Mad Dog : \n*''Dawn of the Seventh Sun'' (1969) -- by Mad Dog<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/dawn-of-the-seventh-sun-mw0001005301|title=Dawn of the Seventh Sun - Mad Dog - Songs, Reviews, Credits - AllMusic|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\n; [[Heart (band)|Heart]] :\n*''[[Dreamboat Annie]]'' (1975) \n*''[[Little Queen]]'' (1977) \n*''[[Magazine (Heart album)|Magazine]]'' (1978) \n*''[[Dog & Butterfly (album)|Dog and Butterfly]]'' (1978) \n*''[[Bebe Le Strange]]'' (1980) \n*''[[Private Audition]]'' (1982) \n*''[[Passionworks]]'' (1983) \n*''[[Heart (Heart album)|Heart]]'' (1985) \n*''[[Bad Animals]]'' (1987) \n*''[[Brigade (album)|Brigade]]'' (1990) \n*''[[Desire Walks On]]'' (1993) \n*''[[The Road Home (Heart album)|The Road Home]]'' (1995)\n\n; [[Dixon House Band]] : \n*''[[Fighting Alone]]'' (1979) \n*''[[Masked Madness]]'' (1981)\n\n; [[Paul Rodgers]] :\n*''[[Live in Glasgow (Paul Rodgers album)|Paul Rodgers: Live in Glasgow]]'' (2007)\n\n; [[Bad Company]] : \n*''[[Hard Rock Live (album)|Hard Rock Live]]'' (2010) \n*''[[Live at Wembley (Bad Company album)|Live at Wembley]]'' (2011)\n\n; Solo :\n*''[[Secret Weapon (Howard Leese album)|Secret Weapon]]'' (2009) - With [[Keith Emerson]] and Paul Rodgers.\n\n; Others :\n*''[[Randy Meisner (1982 album)|Randy Meisner]]'' (1982) -- by [[Randy Meisner]]\n*''[[The Thirteenth Dream]] (aka Spirit of '84)'' (1984) -- by [[Spirit (band)|Spirit]]\n*''[[Dangerous Curves (album)|Dangerous Curves]]'' (1991) -- by [[Lita Ford]]\n*''There Must Be A Place'' (1993) -- by Bananafish<ref>[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950106&slug=2097990 Bananafish: Energetic Sound, Hopeful Music], 6 January 1995, The Seattle Times.</ref>\n* ''The Yellow Album'' by The Simpsons. Lead & rhythm guitar on ''Sisters Are Doin' It For Themselves'' : https://www.discogs.com/fr/The-Simpsons-The-Yellow-Album/release/1092354\n\n==Notes==\n<!-- [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] -->\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n*Fjestad S.P. (ed.) Zachary R. (2008) ''Blue Book of Electric Guitars'' 11th Edition, Illustrated, Publisher: Alfred Publishing, {{ISBN|1-886768-73-0}}, {{ISBN|978-1-886768-73-4}} pp.&nbsp;599\n*York, William (ed.) (1982) \"Leese, Howard\" ''Who's Who in Rock Music'' Charles Scribner's Sons, New York, {{ISBN|0-684-17343-3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070807102424/http://www.howardleese.com/apps/content/biography.asp \"Howard Leese biography\"] Official Website of Howard Leese\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110717084604/http://brigade.monger.net/howie.html \"Howie's Page\"], ''BebeLeStrange's Ann and Nancy Wilson Site'' by Todd Kinzey\n*{{Cite web |url=http://207.168.168.83/interviews01/howard_leese_interview.htm |title=Interview with Howard Leese |access-date=July 30, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050406201546/http://207.168.168.83/interviews01/howard_leese_interview.htm |archive-date=April 6, 2005 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }} ''Classic Rock Revisited''\n\n{{Heart (band)}}\n{{Bad Company}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leese, Howard}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Record producers from California]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Music directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Hollywood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Heart (band) members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American keyboardists]]\n[[Category:Frontiers Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "188.141.87.103", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_Leese"}
{"title_page": "Invasion of Iceland", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n |conflict    = Invasion of Iceland\n |partof      = [[World War II]]\n |image       = Iceland invasion targets.png\n |image_size  = 300\n |caption     = British aims were to destroy landing grounds (blue) and secure harbours\n |date        = {{start date|1940|05|10|df=y}}\n |place       = Iceland\n |result      = [[Occupation of Iceland]]\n |combatant1  = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n |combatant2  = {{flagdeco|Iceland}} [[Kingdom of Iceland|Iceland]]\n |commander1  = [[Robert Sturges]]\n |commander2  = {{ubl|[[Hermann J\u00f3nasson]]|Einar Arnalds}}\n |strength1   = {{ubl|746 [[Royal Marines]]|4 warships}}\n |strength2   = {{ubl|60 police|300 reservists}}\n |casualties1 = 1 suicide\n |casualties2 = None\n |campaignbox = {{Scandinavia in World War II}}\n}}\n\nThe '''invasion of Iceland''' (codenamed \"Operation Fork\") by the [[Royal Navy]] and [[Royal Marines]] occurred on 10 May 1940, during [[World War II]]. The invasion was performed because the British government feared that [[Iceland]] would be used by the Germans, who had recently [[German invasion of Denmark (1940)|overrun Denmark]], which was in [[personal union]] with Iceland and which had previously been largely responsible for Iceland's foreign policy. The [[Government of Iceland]] issued a protest, charging that its neutrality had been \"flagrantly violated\" and \"its independence infringed\".{{uncited quote|date=May 2019}}\n\nAt the start of the war, the UK imposed strict export controls on Icelandic goods, preventing profitable shipments to Germany, as part of its naval blockade. The UK offered assistance to Iceland, seeking co-operation \"as a belligerent and an ally\",{{uncited quote|date=May 2019}} but [[Reykjav\u00edk]] refused and reaffirmed its neutrality. The German diplomatic presence in Iceland, along with the island's strategic importance, alarmed the UK government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sonic.net/~bstone/history/iceland.shtml |title=Iceland in the Second World War |accessdate=22 June 2008 |last=Stone |first=Bill |year=1998 |publisher=Stone & Stone}}</ref>\n\nAfter failing to persuade the Icelandic government to join the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]], the UK invaded on the morning of 10 May 1940. The initial force of 746 Royal Marines commanded by Colonel [[Robert Sturges]] disembarked at the capital Reykjav\u00edk. Meeting no resistance, the troops moved quickly to disable communication networks, secure strategic locations, and arrest German citizens. Requisitioning local transport, the troops moved to [[Hvalfj\u00f6r\u00f0ur]], [[Kalda\u00f0arnes]], [[Sandskei\u00f0]], and [[Akranes]] to secure potential landing areas against the possibility of a German counterattack.\n\n== Invasion ==\n\n=== Background ===\n{{Further|Iceland during World War II}}\n{{History of Iceland}}\nDuring 1918, after a long period of Danish rule, Iceland had become an independent state in [[personal union]] with the Danish king and with common foreign affairs.{{sfn|Karlsson|2000|p=283}} The newly initiated [[Kingdom of Iceland]] declared itself a [[neutral country]] without a defence force.{{sfn|Karlsson|2000|p=283}} The treaty of union allowed for a revision to begin during 1941 and for unilateral termination three years after that, if no agreement was made.{{sfn|Karlsson|2000|p=283}} By 1928, all Icelandic political parties were in agreement that the union treaty would be terminated as soon as possible.{{sfn|Karlsson|2000|p=319}}\n\nOn 9 April 1940, German forces began [[Operation Weser\u00fcbung]], invading both Norway and Denmark. Denmark was subdued within a day and [[Occupation of Denmark|occupied]]. On the same day, the British government sent a message to the Icelandic government, stating that the UK was willing to assist Iceland in maintaining its independence but would require facilities in Iceland to do so. Iceland was invited to join the UK in the war \"as a belligerent and an ally.\" The Icelandic government rejected the offer.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=34}} On the next day, 10 April, the Icelandic parliament, the [[Al\u00feingi]] (or Althing), declared Danish King [[Christian X]] unable to perform his constitutional duties and assigned them to the government of Iceland, along with all other responsibilities previously performed by Denmark on behalf of Iceland.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=272}}\n\nWith [[British occupation of the Faroe Islands in World War II|Operation Valentine]] on 12 April 1940, the British occupied the [[Faroe Islands]]. After the German invasion of Denmark and Norway, the British government became increasingly concerned that Germany would soon try to establish a military presence in Iceland. They felt that this would constitute an intolerable threat to British control of the North [[Atlantic]]. Just as importantly, the British were eager to obtain bases in Iceland for themselves to strengthen their [[Northern Patrol]].{{sfn|Bittner|1983|pp=33\u201334}}\n\n=== Planning ===\nAs the military situation in Norway deteriorated, the [[Admiralty]] came to the conclusion that the UK could no longer do without bases in Iceland. On 6 May, [[Winston Churchill]] presented the case to the [[War Cabinet#Second World War|War Cabinet]]. Churchill maintained that if further negotiations with the Icelandic government were attempted, the Germans might learn of them and act first. A surer and more effective solution was to land troops unannounced and present the Icelandic government with a ''[[:wikt:fait accompli|fait accompli]]''. The War Cabinet approved the plan.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=38}}\n\nThe expedition was organised hastily and haphazardly.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=40}} Much of the operational planning was conducted en route. The force was supplied with few maps, most of poor quality, with one of them having been drawn from memory. No one of the expedition was fully fluent with the [[Icelandic language]].{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=363}}\n\nThe British planned to land all of their forces at Reykjav\u00edk. There, they would overcome any resistance and defeat local Germans.{{cn|date=December 2019}} To guard against a German counterattack by sea, they would secure the harbour and send troops by land to nearby [[Hvalfj\u00f6r\u00f0ur]]. The British were also worried that the Germans might airlift troops, as they had done with great success in their [[Norwegian Campaign]]. To guard against this, troops would drive east to the landing grounds at [[Sandskei\u00f0]] and [[Kalda\u00f0arnes]]. Lastly, troops would be sent by land to the harbour at [[Akureyri]] and the landing ground at Melger\u00f0i in the north of the country.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=353}}\n\nThe UK [[Naval Intelligence Division]] (NID) expected resistance from three possible sources. Local Germans, who were thought to have some arms, might resist or even attempt some sort of coup. In addition, a German invasion force might already be prepared or begun immediately after the British landings. The NID also expected resistance from the Reykjav\u00edk police, consisting of some [[Military history of Iceland#Independent Iceland|60 armed men]]. If by chance a Danish patrol vessel were present in Reykjav\u00edk, the Danish sailors might assist the defenders.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=354}}{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=36}} This concern was needless, as the only Danish naval vessels abroad were in [[Greenland in World War II|Greenland]].<ref name=NSP>{{cite web |url=http://www.navalhistory.dk/English/History/1939_1945/us_safari.htm |title=The Big Scuttle \u2013 August 29, 1943 |first=S\u00f8ren |last=N\u00f8rby |website=Naval History.dk |year=2015 |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Operation Fork ===\n\n==== Force Sturges ====\n[[File:Christian X of Denmark.jpg|thumb|King [[Christian X of Denmark|Christian X]] was said by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' to be \"less unpopular in Iceland than any other Danish sovereign has ever been\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=Iceland: Nobody's Baby|journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=22 April 1940|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,763855,00.html}}</ref>]]\nOn 3 May 1940, the [[43 Commando|2nd Royal Marine Battalion]] in [[Bisley, Surrey]] received orders from London to be ready to move at two hours' notice for an unknown destination. The battalion had been activated only the month before. Though there was a nucleus of active service officers, the troops were new recruits and only partially trained.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=41}} There was a shortage of weapons, which consisted only of rifles, pistols, and bayonets, while 50 of the marines had only just received their rifles and had not had a chance to fire them. On 4 May, the battalion received some modest additional equipment in the form of [[Bren light machine gun]]s, [[anti-tank gun]]s, and [[2-inch mortar]]s. With no time to spare, zeroing of the weapons and initial familiarisation shooting would have to be conducted at sea.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=352}}\n\nAssisting arms provided to the force consisted of two [[3.7 inch Mountain Howitzer|3.7 inch mountain howitzers]], four [[QF 2 pounder naval gun]]s, and two 4-inch coastal defence guns.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=352}} The guns were manned by troops from the artillery divisions of the Navy and the marines, none of whom had ever fired them.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=352}} They lacked searchlights, communication equipment, and gun directors.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}\n\nColonel [[Robert Sturges]] was assigned to command the force. Aged 49, he was a highly regarded veteran of [[World War I]], having fought in the [[battle of Gallipoli]] and the [[battle of Jutland]].{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=352}} He was accompanied by a small intelligence detachment commanded by Major Humphrey Quill and a diplomatic mission managed by [[Charles Howard Smith]].{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=41}} Excluding those, the invasion force consisted of 746 troops.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=305}}\n\n==== Journey to Iceland ====\n[[File:HMS Berwick (65).jpg|thumb|{{HMS|Berwick|65|6}} was the command ship of the operation]]\nOn 6 May, Force Sturges boarded trains for [[Greenock]] on the [[Firth of Clyde]]. To avoid drawing attention to itself, the force was divided into two different trains for the journey,{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=361}} but due to delays in rail travel, the troops arrived at the railway station in Greenock about the same time, losing the small degree of anonymity desired.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=361}} Additionally, security had been compromised by a dispatch [[Cleartext|uncoded]] and by the time the troops arrived in Greenock, many people{{who|date=May 2018}} knew that the destination was Iceland.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=41}}\n\nOn the morning of 7 May, the force headed to the harbour in Greenock, where they found the cruisers {{HMS|Berwick|65|2}} and {{HMS|Glasgow|C21|2}}, intended to take them to Iceland. Boarding commenced but was fraught with problems and delays. Departure was delayed until 8 May, and even then a large amount of equipment and supplies had to be left on the piers.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=362}}\n\nAt 04:00 on 8 May, the cruisers departed for Iceland. They were accompanied by an anti-submarine escort consisting of the destroyers {{HMS|Fearless|H67|2}} and {{HMS|Fortune|H70|2}}. The cruisers were not designed to transport a force of the size assigned to them, and conditions were cramped.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=363}} Despite reasonably good weather, many of the marines developed severe [[seasickness]]. The voyage was used as planned for calibration and familiarisation with the newly acquired weapons.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=364}} One of the newly recruited marines committed suicide en route.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|pp=374\u2013375}}{{sfn|Miller|2003|p=88}} The voyage was  uneventful otherwise.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}\n\n{{quote|In May 1940 we transported Royal Marines to Iceland and the island was occupied on the 10th May to prevent the occupation by a German force. A number of German civilians and technicians were made prisoners and transported back to the United Kingdom. Very rough seas were encountered on passage to Iceland and the majority of the marines cluttered gangways and mess-decks throughout the ship, prostrate with seasickness. One unfortunate marine committed suicide.|Stan Foreman, petty officer of HMS ''Berwick''<ref>{{cite web |title=WW2 People's War: Stan Foreman's War Years 1939\u20131945 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/ww2peopleswar/stories/00/a8604100.shtml| accessdate=28 July 2007 |date=17 January 2006 |publisher=BBC}}</ref>}}\n\n==== Surprise is lost ====\n[[File:Supermarine Walrus.jpg|thumb|[[Supermarine Walrus]] aircraft \u2013 though it proved ultimately unsuitable for operations in Iceland, it had the advantage that it could land almost anywhere{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=76}}]]\nAt 01:47, Icelandic time, on 10 May, HMS ''Berwick'' used its [[aircraft catapult]] to launch a [[Supermarine Walrus]] reconnaissance aircraft.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=379}} The principal aim of the flight was to scout the vicinity of Reykjav\u00edk for enemy submarines, which the Naval Intelligence Division had convinced itself were operating out of Icelandic harbours.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=379}}\n\nThe Walrus was given orders not to fly over Reykjav\u00edk but&nbsp;\u2013 either accidentally or as the result of a miscommunication&nbsp;\u2013 it flew several circles over the town, making considerable noise.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=380}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=15}} At this time, Iceland possessed no aeroplanes of its own, so this unusual event awoke and alerted a number of people.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=15}} [[Prime Minister of Iceland]] [[Hermann J\u00f3nasson]] was alerted about the aircraft,{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=17}} as were the [[Icelandic Police]]. The acting chief of police, Einar Arnalds, surmised that it most likely originated from a British warship bringing the expected new ambassador.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=17}} This was correct, though it was not the whole story.\n\nWerner Gerlach, the German consul, was also alerted to the aircraft. Suspecting what was about to happen, he drove down to the harbour with a German associate.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|pp=380\u2013384}} With the use of binoculars, he confirmed his fears and then hurried back.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=11}} At home, he arranged for the burning of his documents and tried unsuccessfully to reach the [[Minister for Foreign Affairs of Iceland|Icelandic foreign minister]] by telephone.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=30\u201332}}\n\n==== Down at the harbour ====\nAt 03:40, an Icelandic policeman saw a small fleet of warships approaching the harbour, but could not discern their nationality. He notified his superior, who notified Einar Arnalds, the acting chief of police.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=15\u201317}} The laws of neutrality to which Iceland had committed forbade more than three warships from a belligerent nation from making use of a neutral harbour at the same time. Any aeroplanes from such ships were forbidden from flying over neutral territorial waters.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=17}} Seeing that the approaching fleet was about to violate Icelandic neutrality in two ways, Arnalds began to investigate.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=17}} Down at the harbour, he viewed the ships for himself and decided they were probably British. He contacted the foreign ministry, which confirmed that he should go out to the fleet and announce to its commander that he was in violation of Icelandic neutrality.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=22\u201323}} Customs officers were ordered to prepare a boat.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=22\u201323}}\n\nMeanwhile, marines on ''Berwick'' were being ordered aboard ''Fearless'', which would take them to the harbour. The seasickness and inexperience of the troops were causing delays and the officers were becoming frustrated.{{sfn|Miller|2003|p=88}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=10}} Just before five o'clock in the morning, ''Fearless'', loaded with about 400 marines, began moving toward the harbour.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=24\u201325}} A small crowd had assembled, including several policemen still waiting for the customs boat. The British consul had received advance notice of the invasion and was waiting with his associates to assist the troops when they arrived. Uncomfortable with the crowd, Consul Shepherd turned to the Icelandic police. \"Would you mind ... getting the crowd to stand back a bit, so that the soldiers can get off the destroyer?\" he asked. \"Certainly,\" came the reply.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=24\u201325}}\n\nThe ''Fearless'' started disembarking immediately once it docked.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=25}} Arnalds asked to speak with the captain of the destroyer, but was refused.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=28}} He then hastened to report to the Prime Minister, who ordered him not to interfere with the British troops and to try to prevent conflicts between them and Icelanders.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=28}} Down at the harbour, some of the locals protested against the arrival of the British. One Icelander snatched a rifle from a marine and stuffed a cigarette in it. He then threw it back to the marine and told him to be careful with it. An officer arrived to scold the marine.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=27}}\n\n==== Operations in Reykjav\u00edk ====\nThe British forces began their operations in Reykjav\u00edk by posting a guard at the post office and attaching a flyer to the door.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=33}} The flyer explained in broken Icelandic that British forces were occupying the city and asked for co-operation in dealing with local Germans.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=34}} The offices of [[S\u00edminn]] (telecommunication service), [[R\u00daV]] (broadcasting service), and the Meteorological Office were quickly occupied by the British to prevent news of the invasion from reaching Berlin.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=35}}\n\nMeanwhile, high priority was assigned to the capture of the German consulate. Arriving at the consulate, the British troops were relieved to find no sign of resistance and simply knocked on the door. Consul Gerlach opened, protested against the invasion, and reminded the British that Iceland was a neutral country. He was reminded, in turn, that Denmark had also been a neutral country.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=39}} The British discovered a fire upstairs in the building and found a pile of documents burning in the consul's bathtub. They extinguished the fire and salvaged a substantial number of records.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=43}}\n\nThe British had also expected resistance from the crew of ''Bahia Blanca'', a German freighter which had hit an iceberg in the [[Denmark Strait]] and whose 62-man crew had been rescued by an Icelandic trawler. The Naval Intelligence Division believed the Germans were actually reserve crews for the German submarines they thought were operating out of Iceland.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=356}} The unarmed Germans were captured without incident.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=47}}\n\n== Outcome ==\n{{main|Occupation of Iceland}}\n{{more citations needed|section|date=May 2017}}\n\n[[File:Icelandic Army 1940.png|thumb|Icelandic police officers undergoing firearms instruction in 1940]]\n\nOn the evening of 10 May, the [[government of Iceland]] issued a protest, charging that its neutrality had been \"flagrantly violated\" and \"its independence infringed\", noting that compensation would be expected for all damage done. The British promised compensation, favourable business agreements, non-interference in Icelandic affairs, and the withdrawal of all forces at the end of the war. In the following days, air defence equipment was deployed in Reykjav\u00edk and a detachment of troops sent to [[Akureyri]]. However, the initial invasion force was ill-equipped, only partially trained and insufficient to the task of occupation and defence of the island.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=41}}\n\nOn 17 May, 4,000 additional troops of the [[Canadian Army]] arrived to relieve the marines. In July, elements of the [[2nd Canadian Division]] and [[3rd Canadian Division]] were landed. Commonwealth occupation forces eventually totalled 25,000 infantry with elements from the [[Royal Air Force]], Royal Navy and [[Royal Canadian Navy]].{{sfn|Fairchild|2000|pp=73\u201397}} One year after the invasion, forces from the still officially neutral United States were stationed on the island by agreement with the Icelandic government, relieving the bulk of British ground forces. U.S. forces grew considerably after the US joined the war on 7 December 1941, reaching as many as 30,000 army, navy and air force personnel at any one time. The RAF and RCAF continued to operate from two [[Royal Air Force station]]s through to the end of the war.\n\nThe UK invaded to forestall a German occupation, to provide a base for naval and air patrols, and to protect merchant shipping lanes from North America to Europe. In this the invasion was successful. However, the presence of British, Canadian, and US troops had a lasting impact on the country. Foreign troop numbers in some years equalled 25 percent of the population or almost 50 percent of the native male population. Icelanders were and remain divided about the war and occupation&nbsp;\u2013 what is sometimes referred to as \"blessa\u00f0 str\u00ed\u00f0i\u00f0\" or \"the Blessed War\". Some point to the subsequent economic revival, others to loss of sovereignty and social upheaval.\n\nThe occupation required the building of a network of roads, hospitals, harbours, airfields and bridges across the country, and this did have an enormous positive economic impact. However, the Icelanders severely censured the sexual relationships between troops and local women, which were causing considerable controversy and political turmoil.{{cn|date=December 2019}} Women were often accused of prostitution and of being traitors. Two-hundred and fifty-five children were born from these [[\u00c1standi\u00f0|liaisons]], the {{lang-is|\u00e1standsb\u00f6rn|lit=children of the situation|label=none}}.\n\nIn 1941, the Icelandic Minister of the Judiciary investigated \"The Situation\", and the police tracked 500+ women who had been having sex with the soldiers.{{cn|date=December 2019}} Many were upset that the foreign troops were \"taking away\" women, friends, and family. During 1942 two facilities opened to house such women who had relations with the soldiers. Both closed within a year, after investigations determined that most liaisons were consensual. About 332 Icelandic women married foreign soldiers.\n\nDuring the occupation, on 17 June 1944, Iceland declared itself a republic. The [[Keflav\u00edk Agreement]] signed during 1946 between the US and the Republic of Iceland stipulated that the American army would leave the country within six months, and Iceland would take possession of the Keflav\u00edk Airport. This did not happen for decades, and a substantial US military presence remained in Iceland until 30 September 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icelandicroots.com/post/2014/11/11/the-occupation-of-iceland-during-world-war-ii/|title=The Occupation of Iceland During World War II|last=|first=|date=November 11, 2014|website=Icelandic Roots|publisher=Icelandic Roots|access-date=July 1, 2016}}</ref> At the end of hostilities most British facilities were given to the Icelandic government.\n\nAlthough the British action was to forestall any risk of a German invasion, there is no evidence that the Germans had an invasion planned. There was, however, German ''interest'' in seizing Iceland. In a postwar interview, [[Walter Warlimont]] claimed that \"Hitler definitely was interested in occupying Iceland prior to [British] occupation. In the first place, he wanted to prevent \"anyone else\" from coming there; and, in the second place, he also wanted to use Iceland as an air base for the protection of our submarines operating in that area\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=5347798|title = Hlutleysi \u00cdslands \u00e1 hverfandi hveli|last = Whitehead|first = \u00de\u00f3r|date = 2006|journal = Saga|page = 22|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160402041200/http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=5347798|archive-date = 2 April 2016|url-status = dead|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter the British invasion, the Germans composed a report to examine the feasibility of seizing Iceland, proposed as [[Operation Ikarus]]. The report found that while an invasion could be successful, maintaining supply lines would be too costly and the benefits of holding Iceland would not outweigh the costs (there was, for instance, insufficient infrastructure for aircraft in Iceland).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Hverjar voru \u00e1\u00e6tlanir \u00dej\u00f3\u00f0verja um a\u00f0 r\u00e1\u00f0ast inn \u00ed \u00cdsland \u00ed seinni heimsstyrj\u00f6ldinni?|url = http://www.visindavefur.is/svar.php?id=5103|accessdate = 2015-09-24}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[\u00c1standi\u00f0]]'', a term about the influence of British and U.S. soldiers on Icelandic women\n* [[British occupation of the Faroe Islands]]\n* [[Expansion operations and planning of the Axis Powers]]\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book|last = Bittner|first = D. F.|date = 1983|title = The Lion and the White Falcon: Britain and Iceland in the World War II Era|location = Hamden|publisher = Archon Books|isbn = 0-208-01956-1|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Fairchild|first = B.|date = 2000|chapter = Decision to Land United States Forces in Iceland, 1941|chapterurl = http://www.history.army.mil/books/70-7_03.htm|title = Command Decisions|publisher = [[Army Center for Military History|CMH]]|id = Pub 70-7|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Karlsson|first = G.|date = 2000|title = Iceland's 1100 Years: History of a Marginal Society|location = London|publisher = Hurst|isbn=1-85065-420-4|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Miller|first = J.|date = 2003|title = The North Atlantic Front: Orkney, Shetland, Faroe and Iceland at War |location = Edinburgh|publisher = Birlinn|isbn = 1-84341-011-7|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Whitehead|first = \u00de.|authorlink=\u00de\u00f3r Whitehead|date = 1995|title = Milli vonar og \u00f3tta: \u00cdsland \u00ed s\u00ed\u00f0ari heimsstyrj\u00f6ld|location = Reykjav\u00edk|publisher = Vaka-Helgafell|isbn = 9979-2-0317-X|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Whitehead|first = \u00de.|date = 1999|title = Bretarnir koma: \u00cdsland \u00ed s\u00ed\u00f0ari heimsstyrj\u00f6ld|location = Reykjav\u00edk|publisher = Vaka-Helgafell|isbn = 9979-2-1435-X|ref = harv}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last=Stacey |first=C. P. |authorlink=C. P.  Stacey |year=1970 |title=Arms, Men and Governments: The War Policies of Canada, 1939\u20131945 |url=https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/themes/defence/caf/militaryhistory/dhh/official/book-1970-policies-ww2-en.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=14 June 2019 |location=Ottawa |publisher=Queen's Printer |id=D2-5569 |oclc=317692687}}\n* {{cite book |last=Stacey |first=C. P. |year=1955 |series=Official History of the Canadian Army in the Second World War |title=Six Years of War |volume=I |url=https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/themes/defence/caf/militaryhistory/dhh/official/book-1955-army-ww2-1-en.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=14 June 2019 |location=Ottawa |publisher=Queen's Printer |oclc=757709489}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/timeline/410707awp.html \"Franklin D. Roosevelt's message to Congress on the US occupation of Iceland\"], U.S. State Department (7 July 1941).\n\n{{Iceland topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1940 in Iceland]]\n[[Category:Allied occupation of Europe|Iceland]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Battle of the Atlantic]]\n[[Category:British military occupations|Iceland]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1940]]\n[[Category:Iceland in World War II]]\n[[Category:Iceland\u2013United Kingdom military relations]]\n[[Category:Invasions by the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Invasions of Iceland]]\n[[Category:History of the Royal Marines]]\n[[Category:Military history of Iceland during World War II]]\n[[Category:World War II invasions|Iceland]]\n[[Category:World War II occupied territories|Iceland]]\n[[Category:World War II operations of the Western European Theatre]]\n[[Category:Military history of Canada during World War II]]\n[[Category:Battles and operations of World War II involving the United Kingdom|I]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n |conflict    = Invasion of Iceland\n |partof      = [[World War II]]\n |image       = Iceland invasion targets.png\n |image_size  = 300\n |caption     = British aims were to destroy landing grounds (blue) and secure harbours\n |date        = {{start date|1940|05|10|df=y}}\n |place       = Iceland\n |result      = [[Occupation of Iceland]]\n |combatant1  = {{flag|United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland}}\n |combatant2  = {{flagdeco|Iceland}} [[Kingdom of Iceland|Iceland]]\n |commander1  = [[Robert Sturges]]\n |commander2  = {{ubl|[[Hermann J\u00f3nasson]]|Einar Arnalds}}\n |strength1   = {{ubl|746 [[Royal Marines]]|4 warships}}\n |strength2   = {{ubl|60 police|300 reservists}}\n |casualties1 = 1 suicide\n |casualties2 = None\n |campaignbox = {{Scandinavia in World War II}}\n}}\n\nThe '''invasion of Iceland''' (codenamed \"Operation Fork\") by the [[Royal Navy]] and [[Royal Marines]] occurred on 10 May 1940, during [[World War II]]. The invasion was performed because the British government feared that [[Iceland]] would be used by the Germans, who had recently [[German invasion of Denmark (1940)|overrun Denmark]], which was in [[personal union]] with Iceland and which had previously been largely responsible for Iceland's foreign policy. The [[Government of Iceland]] issued a protest, charging that its neutrality had been \"flagrantly violated\" and \"its independence infringed\".{{uncited quote|date=May 2019}}\n\nAt the start of the war, the UK imposed strict export controls on Icelandic goods, preventing profitable shipments to Germany, as part of its naval blockade. The UK offered assistance to Iceland, seeking co-operation \"as a belligerent and an ally\",{{uncited quote|date=May 2019}} but [[Reykjav\u00edk]] refused and reaffirmed its neutrality. The German diplomatic presence in Iceland, along with the island's strategic importance, alarmed the UK government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sonic.net/~bstone/history/iceland.shtml |title=Iceland in the Second World War |accessdate=22 June 2008 |last=Stone |first=Bill |year=1998 |publisher=Stone & Stone}}</ref>\n\nAfter failing to persuade the Icelandic government to join the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]], the UK invaded on the morning of 10 May 1940. The initial force of 746 Royal Marines commanded by Colonel [[Robert Sturges]] disembarked at the capital Reykjav\u00edk. Meeting no resistance, the troops moved quickly to disable communication networks, secure strategic locations, and arrest German citizens. Requisitioning local transport, the troops moved to [[Hvalfj\u00f6r\u00f0ur]], [[Kalda\u00f0arnes]], [[Sandskei\u00f0]], and [[Akranes]] to secure potential landing areas against the possibility of a German counterattack.\n\n== Invasion ==\n\n=== Background ===\n{{Further|Iceland during World War II}}\n{{History of Iceland}}\nDuring 1918, after a long period of Danish rule, Iceland had become an independent state in [[personal union]] with the Danish king and with common foreign affairs.{{sfn|Karlsson|2000|p=283}} The newly initiated [[Kingdom of Iceland]] declared itself a [[neutral country]] without a defence force.{{sfn|Karlsson|2000|p=283}} The treaty of union allowed for a revision to begin during 1941 and for unilateral termination three years after that, if no agreement was made.{{sfn|Karlsson|2000|p=283}} By 1928, all Icelandic political parties were in agreement that the union treaty would be terminated as soon as possible.{{sfn|Karlsson|2000|p=319}}\n\nOn 9 April 1940, German forces began [[Operation Weser\u00fcbung]], invading both Norway and Denmark. Denmark was subdued within a day and [[Occupation of Denmark|occupied]]. On the same day, the British government sent a message to the Icelandic government, stating that the UK was willing to assist Iceland in maintaining its independence but would require facilities in Iceland to do so. Iceland was invited to join the UK in the war \"as a belligerent and an ally.\" The Icelandic government rejected the offer.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=34}} On the next day, 10 April, the Icelandic parliament, the [[Al\u00feingi]] (or Althing), declared Danish King [[Christian X]] unable to perform his constitutional duties and assigned them to the government of Iceland, along with all other responsibilities previously performed by Denmark on behalf of Iceland.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=272}}\n\nWith [[British occupation of the Faroe Islands in World War II|Operation Valentine]] on 12 April 1940, the British occupied the [[Faroe Islands]]. After the German invasion of Denmark and Norway, the British government became increasingly concerned that Germany would soon try to establish a military presence in Iceland. They felt that this would constitute an intolerable threat to British control of the North [[Atlantic]]. Just as importantly, the British were eager to obtain bases in Iceland for themselves to strengthen their [[Northern Patrol]].{{sfn|Bittner|1983|pp=33\u201334}}\n\n=== Planning ===\nAs the military situation in Norway deteriorated, the [[Admiralty]] came to the conclusion that the UK could no longer do without bases in Iceland. On 6 May, [[Winston Churchill]] presented the case to the [[War Cabinet#Second World War|War Cabinet]]. Churchill maintained that if further negotiations with the Icelandic government were attempted, the Germans might learn of them and act first. A surer and more effective solution was to land troops unannounced and present the Icelandic government with a ''[[:wikt:fait accompli|fait accompli]]''. The War Cabinet approved the plan.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=38}}\n\nThe expedition was organised hastily and haphazardly.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=40}} Much of the operational planning was conducted en route. The force was supplied with few maps, most of poor quality, with one of them having been drawn from memory. No one of the expedition was fully fluent with the [[Icelandic language]].{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=363}}\n\nThe British planned to land all of their forces at Reykjav\u00edk. There, they would overcome any resistance and defeat local Germans.{{cn|date=December 2019}} To guard against a German counterattack by sea, they would secure the harbour and send troops by land to nearby [[Hvalfj\u00f6r\u00f0ur]]. The British were also worried that the Germans might airlift troops, as they had done with great success in their [[Norwegian Campaign]]. To guard against this, troops would drive east to the landing grounds at [[Sandskei\u00f0]] and [[Kalda\u00f0arnes]]. Lastly, troops would be sent by land to the harbour at [[Akureyri]] and the landing ground at Melger\u00f0i in the north of the country.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=353}}\n\nThe UK [[Naval Intelligence Division]] (NID) expected resistance from three possible sources. Local Germans, who were thought to have some arms, might resist or even attempt some sort of coup. In addition, a German invasion force might already be prepared or begun immediately after the British landings. The NID also expected resistance from the Reykjav\u00edk police, consisting of some [[Military history of Iceland#Independent Iceland|60 armed men]]. If by chance a Danish patrol vessel were present in Reykjav\u00edk, the Danish sailors might assist the defenders.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=354}}{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=36}} This concern was needless, as the only Danish naval vessels abroad were in [[Greenland in World War II|Greenland]].<ref name=NSP>{{cite web |url=http://www.navalhistory.dk/English/History/1939_1945/us_safari.htm |title=The Big Scuttle \u2013 August 29, 1943 |first=S\u00f8ren |last=N\u00f8rby |website=Naval History.dk |year=2015 |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Operation Fork ===\n\n==== Force Sturges ====\n[[File:Christian X of Denmark.jpg|thumb|King [[Christian X of Denmark|Christian X]] was said by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' to be \"less unpopular in Iceland than any other Danish sovereign has ever been\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=Iceland: Nobody's Baby|journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=22 April 1940|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,763855,00.html}}</ref>]]\nOn 3 May 1940, the [[43 Commando|2nd Royal Marine Battalion]] in [[Bisley, Surrey]] received orders from London to be ready to move at two hours' notice for an unknown destination. The battalion had been activated only the month before. Though there was a nucleus of active service officers, the troops were new recruits and only partially trained.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=41}} There was a shortage of weapons, which consisted only of rifles, pistols, and bayonets, while 50 of the marines had only just received their rifles and had not had a chance to fire them. On 4 May, the battalion received some modest additional equipment in the form of [[Bren light machine gun]]s, [[anti-tank gun]]s, and [[2-inch mortar]]s. With no time to spare, zeroing of the weapons and initial familiarisation shooting would have to be conducted at sea.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=352}}\n\nAssisting arms provided to the force consisted of two [[3.7 inch Mountain Howitzer|3.7 inch mountain howitzers]], four [[QF 2 pounder naval gun]]s, and two 4-inch coastal defence guns.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=352}} The guns were manned by troops from the artillery divisions of the Navy and the marines, none of whom had ever fired them.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=352}} They lacked searchlights, communication equipment, and gun directors.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}\n\nColonel [[Robert Sturges]] was assigned to command the force. Aged 49, he was a highly regarded veteran of [[World War I]], having fought in the [[battle of Gallipoli]] and the [[battle of Jutland]].{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=352}} He was accompanied by a small intelligence detachment commanded by Major Humphrey Quill and a diplomatic mission managed by [[Charles Howard Smith]].{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=41}} Excluding those, the invasion force consisted of 746 troops.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=305}}\n\n==== Journey to Iceland ====\n[[File:HMS Berwick (65).jpg|thumb|{{HMS|Berwick|65|6}} was the command ship of the operation]]\nOn 6 May, Force Sturges boarded trains for [[Greenock]] on the [[Firth of Clyde]]. To avoid drawing attention to itself, the force was divided into two different trains for the journey,{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=361}} but due to delays in rail travel, the troops arrived at the railway station in Greenock about the same time, losing the small degree of anonymity desired.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=361}} Additionally, security had been compromised by a dispatch [[Cleartext|uncoded]] and by the time the troops arrived in Greenock, many people{{who|date=May 2018}} knew that the destination was Iceland.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=41}}\n\nOn the morning of 7 May, the force headed to the harbour in Greenock, where they found the cruisers {{HMS|Berwick|65|2}} and {{HMS|Glasgow|C21|2}}, intended to take them to Iceland. Boarding commenced but was fraught with problems and delays. Departure was delayed until 8 May, and even then a large amount of equipment and supplies had to be left on the piers.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=362}}\n\nAt 04:00 on 8 May, the cruisers departed for Iceland. They were accompanied by an anti-submarine escort consisting of the destroyers {{HMS|Fearless|H67|2}} and {{HMS|Fortune|H70|2}}. The cruisers were not designed to transport a force of the size assigned to them, and conditions were cramped.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=363}} Despite reasonably good weather, many of the marines developed severe [[seasickness]]. The voyage was used as planned for calibration and familiarisation with the newly acquired weapons.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=364}} One of the newly recruited marines committed suicide en route.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|pp=374\u2013375}}{{sfn|Miller|2003|p=88}} The voyage was  uneventful otherwise.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=42}}\n\n{{quote|In May 1940 we transported Royal Marines to Iceland and the island was occupied on the 10th May to prevent the occupation by a German force. A number of German civilians and technicians were made prisoners and transported back to the United Kingdom. Very rough seas were encountered on passage to Iceland and the majority of the marines cluttered gangways and mess-decks throughout the ship, prostrate with seasickness. One unfortunate marine committed suicide.|Stan Foreman, petty officer of HMS ''Berwick''<ref>{{cite web |title=WW2 People's War: Stan Foreman's War Years 1939\u20131945 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/ww2peopleswar/stories/00/a8604100.shtml| accessdate=28 July 2007 |date=17 January 2006 |publisher=BBC}}</ref>}}\n\n==== Surprise is lost ====\n[[File:Supermarine Walrus.jpg|thumb|[[Supermarine Walrus]] aircraft \u2013 though it proved ultimately unsuitable for operations in Iceland, it had the advantage that it could land almost anywhere{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=76}}]]\nAt 01:47, Icelandic time, on 10 May, HMS ''Berwick'' used its [[aircraft catapult]] to launch a [[Supermarine Walrus]] reconnaissance aircraft.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=379}} The principal aim of the flight was to scout the vicinity of Reykjav\u00edk for enemy submarines, which the Naval Intelligence Division had convinced itself were operating out of Icelandic harbours.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=379}}\n\nThe Walrus was given orders not to fly over Reykjav\u00edk but&nbsp;\u2013 either accidentally or as the result of a miscommunication&nbsp;\u2013 it flew several circles over the town, making considerable noise.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=380}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=15}} At this time, Iceland possessed no aeroplanes of its own, so this unusual event awoke and alerted a number of people.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=15}} [[Prime Minister of Iceland]] [[Hermann J\u00f3nasson]] was alerted about the aircraft,{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=17}} as were the [[Icelandic Police]]. The acting chief of police, Einar Arnalds, surmised that it most likely originated from a British warship bringing the expected new ambassador.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=17}} This was correct, though it was not the whole story.\n\nWerner Gerlach, the German consul, was also alerted to the aircraft. Suspecting what was about to happen, he drove down to the harbour with a German associate.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|pp=380\u2013384}} With the use of binoculars, he confirmed his fears and then hurried back.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=11}} At home, he arranged for the burning of his documents and tried unsuccessfully to reach the [[Minister for Foreign Affairs of Iceland|Icelandic foreign minister]] by telephone.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=30\u201332}}\n\n==== Down at the harbour ====\nAt 03:40, an Icelandic policeman saw a small fleet of warships approaching the harbour, but could not discern their nationality. He notified his superior, who notified Einar Arnalds, the acting chief of police.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=15\u201317}} The laws of neutrality to which Iceland had committed forbade more than three warships from a belligerent nation from making use of a neutral harbour at the same time. Any aeroplanes from such ships were forbidden from flying over neutral territorial waters.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=17}} Seeing that the approaching fleet was about to violate Icelandic neutrality in two ways, Arnalds began to investigate.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=17}} Down at the harbour, he viewed the ships for himself and decided they were probably British. He contacted the foreign ministry, which confirmed that he should go out to the fleet and announce to its commander that he was in violation of Icelandic neutrality.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=22\u201323}} Customs officers were ordered to prepare a boat.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=22\u201323}}\n\nMeanwhile, marines on ''Berwick'' were being ordered aboard ''Fearless'', which would take them to the harbour. The seasickness and inexperience of the troops were causing delays and the officers were becoming frustrated.{{sfn|Miller|2003|p=88}}{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=10}} Just before five o'clock in the morning, ''Fearless'', loaded with about 400 marines, began moving toward the harbour.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=24\u201325}} A small crowd had assembled, including several policemen still waiting for the customs boat. The British consul had received advance notice of the invasion and was waiting with his associates to assist the troops when they arrived. Uncomfortable with the crowd, Consul Shepherd turned to the Icelandic police. \"Would you mind ... getting the crowd to stand back a bit, so that the soldiers can get off the destroyer?\" he asked. \"Certainly,\" came the reply.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|pp=24\u201325}}\n\nThe ''Fearless'' started disembarking immediately once it docked.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=25}} Arnalds asked to speak with the captain of the destroyer, but was refused.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=28}} He then hastened to report to the Prime Minister, who ordered him not to interfere with the British troops and to try to prevent conflicts between them and Icelanders.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=28}} Down at the harbour, some of the locals protested against the arrival of the British. One Icelander snatched a rifle from a marine and stuffed a cigarette in it. He then threw it back to the marine and told him to be careful with it. An officer arrived to scold the marine.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=27}}\n\n==== Operations in Reykjav\u00edk ====\nThe British forces began their operations in Reykjav\u00edk by posting a guard at the post office and attaching a flyer to the door.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=33}} The flyer explained in broken Icelandic that British forces were occupying the city and asked for co-operation in dealing with local Germans.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=34}} The offices of [[S\u00edminn]] (telecommunication service), [[R\u00daV]] (broadcasting service), and the Meteorological Office were quickly occupied by the British to prevent news of the invasion from reaching Berlin.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=35}}\n\nMeanwhile, high priority was assigned to the capture of the German consulate. Arriving at the consulate, the British troops were relieved to find no sign of resistance and simply knocked on the door. Consul Gerlach opened, protested against the invasion, and reminded the British that Iceland was a neutral country. He was reminded, in turn, that Denmark had also been a neutral country.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=39}} The British discovered a fire upstairs in the building and found a pile of documents burning in the consul's bathtub. They extinguished the fire and salvaged a substantial number of records.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=43}}\n\nThe British had also expected resistance from the crew of ''Bahia Blanca'', a German freighter which had hit an iceberg in the [[Denmark Strait]] and whose 62-man crew had been rescued by an Icelandic trawler. The Naval Intelligence Division believed the Germans were actually reserve crews for the German submarines they thought were operating out of Iceland.{{sfn|Whitehead|1995|p=356}} The unarmed Germans were captured without incident.{{sfn|Whitehead|1999|p=47}}\n\n== Outcome ==\n{{main|Occupation of Iceland}}\n{{more citations needed|section|date=May 2017}}\n\n[[File:Icelandic Army 1940.png|thumb|Icelandic police officers undergoing firearms instruction in 1940]]\n\nOn the evening of 10 May, the [[government of Iceland]] issued a protest, charging that its neutrality had been \"flagrantly violated\" and \"its independence infringed\", noting that compensation would be expected for all damage done. The British promised compensation, favourable business agreements, non-interference in Icelandic affairs, and the withdrawal of all forces at the end of the war. In the following days, air defence equipment was deployed in Reykjav\u00edk and a detachment of troops sent to [[Akureyri]]. However, the initial invasion force was ill-equipped, only partially trained and insufficient to the task of occupation and defence of the island.{{sfn|Bittner|1983|p=41}}\n\nOn 17 May, 4,000 additional troops of the [[Canadian Army]] arrived to relieve the marines. In July, elements of the [[2nd Canadian Division]] and [[3rd Canadian Division]] were landed. Commonwealth occupation forces eventually totalled 25,000 infantry with elements from the [[Royal Air Force]], Royal Navy and [[Royal Canadian Navy]].{{sfn|Fairchild|2000|pp=73\u201397}} One year after the invasion, forces from the still officially neutral United States were stationed on the island by agreement with the Icelandic government, relieving the bulk of British ground forces. U.S. forces grew considerably after the US joined the war on 7 December 1941, reaching as many as 30,000 army, navy and air force personnel at any one time. The RAF and RCAF continued to operate from two [[Royal Air Force station]]s through to the end of the war.\n\nThe UK invaded to forestall a German occupation, to provide a base for naval and air patrols, and to protect merchant shipping lanes from North America to Europe. In this the invasion was successful. However, the presence of British, Canadian, and US troops had a lasting impact on the country. Foreign troop numbers in some years equalled 25 percent of the population or almost 50 percent of the native male population. Icelanders were and remain divided about the war and occupation&nbsp;\u2013 what is sometimes referred to as \"blessa\u00f0 str\u00ed\u00f0i\u00f0\" or \"the Blessed War\". Some point to the subsequent economic revival, others to loss of sovereignty and social upheaval.\n\nThe occupation required the building of a network of roads, hospitals, harbours, airfields and bridges across the country, and this did have an enormous positive economic impact. However, the Icelanders severely censured the sexual relationships between troops and local women, which were causing considerable controversy and political turmoil.{{cn|date=December 2019}} Women were often accused of prostitution and of being traitors. Two-hundred and fifty-five children were born from these [[\u00c1standi\u00f0|liaisons]], the {{lang-is|\u00e1standsb\u00f6rn|lit=children of the situation|label=none}}.\n\nIn 1941, the Icelandic Minister of the Judiciary investigated \"The Situation\", and the police tracked 500+ women who had been having sex with the soldiers.{{cn|date=December 2019}} Many were upset that the foreign troops were \"taking away\" women, friends, and family. During 1942 two facilities opened to house such women who had relations with the soldiers. Both closed within a year, after investigations determined that most liaisons were consensual. About 332 Icelandic women married foreign soldiers.\n\nDuring the occupation, on 17 June 1944, Iceland declared itself a republic. The [[Keflav\u00edk Agreement]] signed during 1946 between the US and the Republic of Iceland stipulated that the American army would leave the country within six months, and Iceland would take possession of the Keflav\u00edk Airport. This did not happen for decades, and a substantial US military presence remained in Iceland until 30 September 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icelandicroots.com/post/2014/11/11/the-occupation-of-iceland-during-world-war-ii/|title=The Occupation of Iceland During World War II|last=|first=|date=November 11, 2014|website=Icelandic Roots|publisher=Icelandic Roots|access-date=July 1, 2016}}</ref> At the end of hostilities most British facilities were given to the Icelandic government.\n\nAlthough the British action was to forestall any risk of a German invasion, there is no evidence that the Germans had an invasion planned. There was, however, German ''interest'' in seizing Iceland. In a postwar interview, [[Walter Warlimont]] claimed that \"Hitler definitely was interested in occupying Iceland prior to [British] occupation. In the first place, he wanted to prevent \"anyone else\" from coming there; and, in the second place, he also wanted to use Iceland as an air base for the protection of our submarines operating in that area\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=5347798|title = Hlutleysi \u00cdslands \u00e1 hverfandi hveli|last = Whitehead|first = \u00de\u00f3r|date = 2006|journal = Saga|page = 22|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160402041200/http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=5347798|archive-date = 2 April 2016|url-status = dead|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter the British invasion, the Germans composed a report to examine the feasibility of seizing Iceland, proposed as [[Operation Ikarus]]. The report found that while an invasion could be successful, maintaining supply lines would be too costly and the benefits of holding Iceland would not outweigh the costs (there was, for instance, insufficient infrastructure for aircraft in Iceland).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Hverjar voru \u00e1\u00e6tlanir \u00dej\u00f3\u00f0verja um a\u00f0 r\u00e1\u00f0ast inn \u00ed \u00cdsland \u00ed seinni heimsstyrj\u00f6ldinni?|url = http://www.visindavefur.is/svar.php?id=5103|accessdate = 2015-09-24}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[\u00c1standi\u00f0]]'', a term about the influence of British and U.S. soldiers on Icelandic women\n* [[British occupation of the Faroe Islands]]\n* [[Expansion operations and planning of the Axis Powers]]\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book|last = Bittner|first = D. F.|date = 1983|title = The Lion and the White Falcon: Britain and Iceland in the World War II Era|location = Hamden|publisher = Archon Books|isbn = 0-208-01956-1|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Fairchild|first = B.|date = 2000|chapter = Decision to Land United States Forces in Iceland, 1941|chapterurl = http://www.history.army.mil/books/70-7_03.htm|title = Command Decisions|publisher = [[Army Center for Military History|CMH]]|id = Pub 70-7|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Karlsson|first = G.|date = 2000|title = Iceland's 1100 Years: History of a Marginal Society|location = London|publisher = Hurst|isbn=1-85065-420-4|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Miller|first = J.|date = 2003|title = The North Atlantic Front: Orkney, Shetland, Faroe and Iceland at War |location = Edinburgh|publisher = Birlinn|isbn = 1-84341-011-7|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Whitehead|first = \u00de.|authorlink=\u00de\u00f3r Whitehead|date = 1995|title = Milli vonar og \u00f3tta: \u00cdsland \u00ed s\u00ed\u00f0ari heimsstyrj\u00f6ld|location = Reykjav\u00edk|publisher = Vaka-Helgafell|isbn = 9979-2-0317-X|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last = Whitehead|first = \u00de.|date = 1999|title = Bretarnir koma: \u00cdsland \u00ed s\u00ed\u00f0ari heimsstyrj\u00f6ld|location = Reykjav\u00edk|publisher = Vaka-Helgafell|isbn = 9979-2-1435-X|ref = harv}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last=Stacey |first=C. P. |authorlink=C. P.  Stacey |year=1970 |title=Arms, Men and Governments: The War Policies of Canada, 1939\u20131945 |url=https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/themes/defence/caf/militaryhistory/dhh/official/book-1970-policies-ww2-en.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=14 June 2019 |location=Ottawa |publisher=Queen's Printer |id=D2-5569 |oclc=317692687}}\n* {{cite book |last=Stacey |first=C. P. |year=1955 |series=Official History of the Canadian Army in the Second World War |title=Six Years of War |volume=I |url=https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/themes/defence/caf/militaryhistory/dhh/official/book-1955-army-ww2-1-en.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=14 June 2019 |location=Ottawa |publisher=Queen's Printer |oclc=757709489}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/timeline/410707awp.html \"Franklin D. Roosevelt's message to Congress on the US occupation of Iceland\"], U.S. State Department (7 July 1941).\n\n{{Iceland topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1940 in Iceland]]\n[[Category:Allied occupation of Europe|Iceland]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Battle of the Atlantic]]\n[[Category:British military occupations|Iceland]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1940]]\n[[Category:Iceland in World War II]]\n[[Category:Iceland\u2013United Kingdom military relations]]\n[[Category:Invasions by the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Invasions of Iceland]]\n[[Category:History of the Royal Marines]]\n[[Category:Military history of Iceland during World War II]]\n[[Category:World War II invasions|Iceland]]\n[[Category:World War II occupied territories|Iceland]]\n[[Category:World War II operations of the Western European Theatre]]\n[[Category:Military history of Canada during World War II]]\n[[Category:Battles and operations of World War II involving the United Kingdom|I]]\n", "name_user": "Elshad", "label": "safe", "comment": "Use common name for UK", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invasion_of_Iceland"}
